<HEAD>'60s Drug Guru Timothy Leary to Have Head Frozen After Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sixties drug guru <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Leary </PERSON> said he's signed up to have his head removed and frozen after he dies for possible resurrection, but he admits the technology is `` a long shot. `` I do n't want to just go belly-up when my <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> runs out,'' said the 67-year-old former <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> psychology professor who once advised the youth of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to `` tune in, turn on and drop out'' with mind-altering drugs. <PERSON> Leary </PERSON> said Thursday he's formalizing a $ 35,000 agreement to have his head preserved for posterity in so-called `` cryonic suspension'' by the <ORGANIZATION> Alcor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Extension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Riverside </LOCATION>. `` It's the second dumbest idea in the world,'' <PERSON> Leary </PERSON> said of cryonics, the practice of freezing the recently dead. `` The first is that you go to the worms. It's a long shot but it's worth a try.'' <ORGANIZATION> Alcor </ORGANIZATION> is best known for a long-running battle with authorities about whether an elderly woman client was actually dead when her head was surgically severed and immersed in liquid nitrogen. A judge backed <ORGANIZATION> Alcor </ORGANIZATION> in its refusal to turn in the head for tests, and the matter remains at a standoff. <PERSON> Leary </PERSON>, who recently has been appearing at colleges and nightclubs after years of relative obscurity, said he has followed developments in cryonics since 1976, when he wrote a paper on 22 alternatives to `` involuntary, irreversible death.'' `` He's been interested the last 30 years in any cutting edge technology,'' explained his agent, <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON>. `` And this, if you'll pardon the expression, is cutting edge technology.'' For his $ 35,000, <PERSON> Leary </PERSON>, who says he is perfecly healthy, would become a member of the non-profit <ORGANIZATION> Alcor </ORGANIZATION> foundation. That gives him the right to have his head surgically removed after death and immersed in liquid nitrogen at minus 320 degrees Fahrenheit. <ORGANIZATION> Alcor </ORGANIZATION> also freezes entire bodies, but <PERSON> Leary </PERSON> said he could n't afford the $ 100,000 price Mainstream scientists scoff at cryonics, but adherents believe the essence of a person's mental or spiritual being resides physically in the brain. That essence could someday be transferred to a mechanically produced or biologically cloned body, said <ORGANIZATION> Alcor </ORGANIZATION>'s president, <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondragon </PERSON>. `` There's about as good a chance that they'll be able to bring you back in 50 years than there is that we'll get a good president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, or that they'll find a cure for the common cold,'' <PERSON> Leary </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Leary </PERSON> does n't think his much-publicized drug use ruined his brain for revival, but is prepared: `` I'd be very happy, if they do n't bring me back, to have it turned over to the neurologists.'' <ORGANIZATION> Alcor </ORGANIZATION> has six heads and two complete bodies frozen in concrete vats of liquid nitrogen, <PERSON> Mondragon </PERSON> said. He said 109 members signed up to be suspended after they die. The controversy over the head of 85-year-old <PERSON> Dora </PERSON> <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> boosted interest in membership and <PERSON> Leary </PERSON>'s endorsement may do the same, said <PERSON> Mondragon </PERSON> `` A lot of people may have negative reactions to Dr. <PERSON> Leary </PERSON>, but people without open minds do n't generally come to us anyway,'' said <PERSON> Mondragon </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
