<HEAD>Allis-Chalmers Agrees to Pay $4.5 Million Penalty For Pollution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Allis-Chalmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to pay the federal government $ 4.5 million to clean up 13 hazardous waste sites in seven states, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announced Friday. The payment agreement was filed in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, where <ORGANIZATION> Allis-Chalmers </ORGANIZATION>, a Milwaukee-based farm equipment manufacturer, is reorganizing under Chapter 11 of the Bankruptcy Code in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankruptcy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The $ 4.5 million payment is subject to approval by the federal court. The agreement was the result of the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s program to make sure certain environmental cleanup issues are addressed when companies reorganize under federal bankruptcy law, said Assistant Attorney General <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marzulla </PERSON> of the Land and Natural Resources Division. <PERSON> Marzulla </PERSON> said the firm pledged to pay the government regardless of other obligations under the reorganization proceedings. The $ 4.5 million will be distributed to the following sites: Maxey Flats Nuclear Disposal Site, <LOCATION> Morehead </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, $ 325,000; <LOCATION> Bluff </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Road </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Landfill </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, $ 15,000; <ORGANIZATION> Peak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, $ 25,000; <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> landfill site, <LOCATION> Gary </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, $ 40,000; Northside Sanitary landfill-Envirochem, <LOCATION> Zionsville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, $ 30,000; <ORGANIZATION> Schmalz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dump </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Site </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, $ 2 million; Ninth Avenue Dump Site, <PERSON> Gary </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, $ 625,000; <ORGANIZATION> Muskego </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sanitary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Landfill </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Muskego </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, $ 375,000; <LOCATION> Brookfield </LOCATION> Sanitary landfill -LRB- Loth Disposal Site -RRB-, <LOCATION> Brookfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, $ 125,000; <ORGANIZATION> Lenz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Lemont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, $ 295,000; <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Scrap, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, $ 625,000; Interstate Transformer, <LOCATION> Ellwood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, $ 10,000; and <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'s Lane Landfill, <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, Ky, $ 10,000.
