<SECOND>PM-Fetal Tissue, Bjt,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Asks Anti-Abortionists If They Can Accept Fetal Tissue
Research</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Committee not expected to arrive at recommendations before
midafternoon EDT; may stand for PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHESDA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Near the end of two days of scholarly talk about the ramifications of allowing intentionally aborted fetuses to be used for medical research, a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> advisory committee member sharpened the issue with a simple question: Will there ever be a medical benefit `` great enough'' for anti-abortionists to drop their opposition to using tissue from induced abortions? `` No,'' <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON>, public affairs director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Right </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> to </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, told <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, chief of neurology at <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. ` No,'' said <PERSON> Judi </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Stafford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>. A few minutes earlier, <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> <PERSON> Duke </PERSON>, co-chairwoman of the <ORGANIZATION> Population </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crisis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> based in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, had acknowledged the strong opposition of anti-abortionists and said she wished there was some way to reach accommodation over the transplant issue. `` But to hold a nation hostage to a minority group who are opposed to abortion is a tragedy,'' she said. `` They must know that even if it -LRB- abortion -RRB- became illegal, it would still be done. It's just not going to go away It has been with us since the written word.'' Another member of the panel of witnesses, <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorovitz </PERSON>, dean of the college of arts and sciences at <ORGANIZATION> Syracuse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, told <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> he empathized with his effort to find common ground but suggested the `` intractable polarity'' of positions just outlined by his fellow panelists showed that would be impossible. In the end, <PERSON> Gorovitz </PERSON> predicted, the special advisory committee will simply have to settle on `` the position for which the arguments are best,'' with the realization that one group or the other will be unhappy. `` There is no way out of that,'' <PERSON> Gorovitz </PERSON> said. Retired federal appeals court judge <PERSON> Arlin </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, the advisory committee chairman, broke the 21-member committee into smaller groups for informal discussions Thursday night and again today. He planned to bring them together late today in hopes they could reach consensus on whether to recommend federal approval of using fetal tissue from induced abortions for research and, if so, what guidelines to recommend to guard against abuses. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> said he hoped the committee could agree enough by the end of the day to allow a rough draft of a document that would be circulated for further discussion with an eye toward having a formal recommendation ready in time for presentation Dec. 1 to a standing <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> committee. Father <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>, a Roman Catholic church leader from <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>, drew a clear distinction between induced abortions and natural abortions in expressing his opposition to using tissue from the former. `` One might say that the American public becomes accomplices after the fact for these induced abortions'' if its institutions embrace policies that could tend to give a medical value to having an abortion, he said. Several committee members used the term `` custom pregnancy'' as a short way of raising the concern that some woman might become pregnant just to produce an aborted fetus for research _ either for financial gain or in an effort to help a sick relative. `` I do n't think people are as callous about abortion as that premise suggests,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murray </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Biomedical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ethics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> at </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Case </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` If we get to that point, I'm deeply worried.'' <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> said he was convinced that guidelines could be drawn to ensure that a woman's decision to have an abortion would be kept totally separate from the decision to allow the remains to be used for research. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Levine </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> told the committee his institution has drawn its own guidelines that would exclude transplanting the tissue of a fetus into a relative of the mother. He said that was done out of safety considerations _ that whatever caused the disease in the relative might somehow be present in the offspring's genes _ but coincidentally also serves to negate concern about `` custom pregnancies.''
</TEXT>
