<FIRST>r w PM-Ozone-Cars     09-16 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ozone-Cars,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Says Emission Controls May Be Better Than Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> says regulations to control the volatility of gasoline and the recovery of gasoline fumes could be twice as effective as originally expected. As a result, cities close to complying with federal clean air standards will get a greater than expected reduction in ozone when <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> adopts the new rules. Implementation of the regulations had been expected to help anti-pollution efforts, but <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said Thursday the benefit would be much greater than previously believed. Earlier EPA calculations had indicated the gasoline regulations would reduce the emission of urban hydrocarbons to the atmosphere by 10 percent to 15 percent, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said. `` It could be as much as twice that,'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said. Some cities are so close to complying with the standard that they had been expected to come into compliance simply through the retirement of older, more-polluting vehicles. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said he did not know how many cities would benefit from the new findings. But those helped the most will be areas where peak readings of ozone are `` in the 0.14 -LRB- parts per million -RRB- range'' and below, he said. Some cities may find that measures such as pollution inspections of cars will be unnecessary. There are 38 cities with peak readings of 0.14 ppm or below on <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s list of the 68 urban and rural areas that have failed to meet the nation's ozone standard. Gasoline fumes react in sunlight with nitrogen oxides from all fuel combustion to produce ozone, which is harmful to the lungs. Ozone is the constituent of urban smog that makes the chest feel tight. The federal standard calls for limiting peak ozone to 0.12 parts per million and limiting excursions above that to no more than one hour per year. Gasoline vapor emissions to the atmosphere will be reduced more than expected because the planned regulations will sharply reduce what analysts call `` running losses,'' or the evaporation of gasoline from the tank and other fuel system components while the car is moving. Current cars must meet strict standards for emission of unburned gasoline vapor out the tailpipe and for evaporation. Evaporation is controlled by a vapor recovery system which stores gasoline vapor in a cannister of activated charcoal until they can be recycled to the tank. It is tested by collecting vapor emitted when a car is stationary, and for this, the agency uses a test fuel whose volatility has remained unchanged since 1975. Actual volatility has increased sharply since then, and on hot days it can overwhelm the cannister. In such circumstances, the car can emit to the atmosphere 25 times more gasoline vapor than is permitted out the exhaust. The volatility standard will reduce these emissions and the vapor recovery regulation will ensure that more of them are captured, agency officials say. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> says this would remove a large source of urban ozone that the agency had not known was there.
</TEXT>
