<HEAD>Boston University Announces Parietal Rules Despite Student Protest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> rejected student protests and issued strict new rules prohibiting students from having overnight guests of the opposite sex and reducing the amount of alcohol in dormitories. The rules were released Thursday, a day after 2,000 students converged on campus for a three-hour demonstration against the visitation policy. `` All of life after 11 p.m. has been banned at <ORGANIZATION> BU </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Jamie </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanbonmatsu </PERSON>, a senior at the <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION>, told the crowd. `` The administration is stunting our growth and development by denying us the right to make decisions.'' Under the new guidelines, some of which go into effect in late fall and others during spring, guests must display identification cards and leave the dormitory by 11 p.m. on weekdays and 1 a.m. on weekends. Overnight stays by members of the same sex will be allowed if roommates agree. But members of the opposite sex will not be allowed overnight. The amount of alcohol allowed into the dorms will be limited to a six-pack of beer and a liter of other alcoholic beverages for students over age 21. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Carleton </PERSON>, a university spokesman, said Wednesday's protest did not faze <ORGANIZATION> BU </ORGANIZATION> officials. `` I do n't think any demonstration would have an effect,'' said <PERSON> Carleton </PERSON>. `` What can have an effect is a reasonable discussion.'' Officials said they based their decision on `` concerns stated by students, staff and parents that residences too often have failed to provide the kind of environment where an individual can quietly study and have his or her right to privacy respected.'' <ORGANIZATION> BU </ORGANIZATION> officials cited problems such as parties, late-night group study and peer pressure to put up with overnight guests. There are 8,700 students housed in university residence halls. Parietal rules were dropped by many American colleges and universities, including <ORGANIZATION> BU </ORGANIZATION>, in the 1960s and'70s.
</TEXT>
