<FIRST>r w PM-WarPowers     09-16 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-War Powers,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Says War Powers Provisions Alterned None Of His Decisions</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former President <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON> says the legal restrictions of the controversial War Powers Act never caused him to change any of the decisions he made during his presidency. `` I did what I felt had to be done,'' the former president told a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s comment came Thursday in response to a question from Sen. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Pressler </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-S.D. </LOCATION>, about whether any of <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s national security decisions were affected by the executive branch restrictions contained in the 1973 law. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> is a strong opponent of the law, as have been all presidents since the measure was enacted over President <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s veto The law was a congressional attempt to check some of the power which legislators felt had greatly deepened the American role in the Vietnam War. The law directs the White House to send <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> a report within 48 hours after <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military personnel are sent to areas of imminent hostilities. Those forces must then be withdrawn within 60 days, or in some cases 90 days, unless <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> votes to allow them to remain. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> told the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> subcommittee </ORGANIZATION> set up to study the War Powers Act that he and his successors sent 19 reports to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> under the law, although the documents were n't submitted under provisions of the act that could trigger the 60-day withdrawal period. He added, `` in the 15 years of the War Powers Resolution, it's never been implemented, never ... It's a dormant piece of legislation. It ought to be repealed.'' But <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> added that `` I'm practical, I do n't think it will be -LRB- repealed -RRB-. I support the kind of amendments'' proposed in a reform backed by leaders of both parties. The changes would eliminate the 60 - or 90-day automatic withdrawal period and would replace the reporting requirement with a requirement that a president consult with <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> leaders about major national security decisions The latest War Powers fights have centered on President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s policy of protecting reflagged Kuwaiti tankers in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has refused to invoke the law. There have been seven votes in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on attempts to force the administration to comply with the law, but all have failed. <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sofaer </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> legal adviser, also argued that the law is unconstitutional. `` It incoporates a view of the relative powers of the political branches of our government, and of their proper roles, that is at odds with the Constitution's scheme and with over 200 years of relatively consistent experience,'' <PERSON> Sofaer </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Sofaer </PERSON> also objected to the 60-day restriction because `` the imposition of arbitrary and inflexible deadlines interferes with the effective and successful completion of the initiative undertaken by the president.'' `` Such limits may signal a divided nation, giving our adversaries a basis for hoping that the president may be forced to desist, or at least feel pressured to do so,'' he explained.
</TEXT>
