<FIRST>r a PM-Hurricane-1900     09-16 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hurricane-1900,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Great 1900 Storm In Galveston Still Considered Greatest U.S.
Disaster</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hurricane Gilbert</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GALVESTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The incessant surf rolled in a little higher than normal and even though it was late summer, the peak time for tropical storms, people were n't too concerned. After all, this was <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION>, the largest and most prosperous town in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, the Wall Steet of the <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION>, and it had weathered storms before. In September 1900, in the days before radio and satellite photographs, people had no idea that out in the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> a monster storm was brewing that would change <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> history and bring death and terror on a scale that never has been seen before or since in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. On Sept. 8, 1900, <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION> was home to nearly 38,000 people. When the sun rose the next day, nearly one-sixth of the city's residents were dead, victims of buildings toppled by winds and waves, drowned in the 15-foot storm surge, mangled by flying debris or washed out to sea The death toll was put at 6,000, but it's uncertain how many thousands of others were lost. `` Nobody knows the complete story of what happened at <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION>; nobody ever will know,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Weems </PERSON> wrote in his classic account of the storm, `` A Weekend in September.'' Ironically, the book, written in 1956, was re-released this month to mark the 88th anniversary of the great <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION> storm. `` Most of them wanted to talk,'' <PERSON> Weems </PERSON> says now, recalling his conversations with storm survivors. `` The tragedies were still with them, but enough time had passed so they could talk about them. `` I got the idea some of them might be paying respect to their dead friends and relatives by talking about them.'' Although <PERSON> Weems </PERSON> believes all the hundreds of survivors he interviewed have died since, <PERSON> Jennie </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> <PERSON> Karboski </PERSON> is among the few still living who were there. And what she remembers most is the water, angrily rising _ and the bodies, floating everywhere. Mrs. <PERSON> Karboski </PERSON> is now 100 and lives with her daughter in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. She was 12 and growing up in <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION> when the storm hit. `` They tried to have mass burials at sea, but the next morning many floated back in on the surf,'' she told the <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chronicle </ORGANIZATION> this week. `` The men had to dig trenches and burn them. My dad said they kept the work crews drunk. They had to.'' After a harrowing journey by rowboat and horse cart, Mrs. <PERSON> Karboski </PERSON>'s family found shelter in a Catholic seminary. Others who survived huddled in a lighthouse or a storm-tossed ship or crammed inside the upper stories of their homes. Others clung to wreckage until the waters receded. Perhaps the most lasting monument to the 1900 storm is the <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION> seawall, a concrete embankment 17 feet above mean low tide built after the great storm to ward off future huge storm surges. It has helped to moderate damage from hurricanes since. A more significant effect, however, was that many businessmen who considered <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION> the hub of activity for <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> decided they would not put themselves through another such storm. They moved inland about 50 miles to a mosquito-infested swamp town called <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, which 88 years later is the nation's fourth-largest city
