<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Dukakis Lines Up With Reagan _ Sort Of</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> switched the other day and decided to release overdue payments to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, it was another sign that as far as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> foreign policy is concerned his views have undergone extensive alteration since he entered the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> nearly eight years ago. Presidential spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> explained the surprising switch on the dues as based on a determination by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> that the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> had `` reformed its operation.'' That does n't alter the fact, however, that one of the tenets of the political philosophy that nurtured <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and gave identity to his pursuit of the presidency was severe skepticism of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. Conservatives always have complained that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> paid a disproportionate share of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> bills while serving as a convenient target of the Soviet bloc and the so-called non-aligned countries. But <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to ante up, and another corner was turned. In his twilight months in the White House only his commitment to guerrillas trying to overthrow the Sandinista government in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> remains uncolored by the pragmatic fact that the Contras are not making much headway. On arms control, after campaigning in 1980 against all major accords with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and putting negotiations on a back burner for months, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> gradually adopted a stance that even diehard opponents grudgingly acknowledged was far friendlier to arms control than they had expected. They still are worried he may try to unravel the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty before heading home to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, but the new 1987 accord to ban intermediate-range nuclear missiles is safely on the books. It stands as the only U.S.-Soviet agreement to eliminate an entire category of nuclear weapons, and it was negotiated on <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s watch. Meanwhile, four summit meetings with Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> have produced a conciliatory stance in the White House that is in striking contrast to early <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> rhetorical flourishes that included castigating <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> as an `` evil empire.'' Until November 1985, he was the first American president since <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON> not to have met with a Soviet leader. Now he has held more one-on-one superpower summits than any of them. Ironically, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has moderated his arms control policy to such an extent that <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who is a liberal Democrat, suggested this week in outlining a nuclear missile strategy agenda that his views were not that far from the president's. The biggest difference is over <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s Strategic Defense Initiative. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said he would `` stop pouring billions and billions of dollars'' into the pursuit of a space-based defense against Soviet ballistic missiles. But he said he would continue a modest research program into possible missile defenses. The Republican candidate, Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who projected himself in 1980 as a moderate alternative to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s deep conservatism, is working overtime, meanwhile, to align himself with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s foreign policy initiatives His pitch essentially is that he would continue along the same course if he is elected. Having been part of the administration, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s job in lining up with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> policies is hardly as difficult as the task confronting <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. But the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> candidate's agenda on weapons moved him closer to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has voiced concerns about the costs of the B-1 bomber and the Midgetman missile, but he endorsed production of the Trident II submarine-launched missile and four other weapons. More significant, perhaps, was his vow that `` We'll use force when it's necessary to protect our territory, our citizens or our vital interests; to meet our treaty commitments; and to deter or to respond to terrorist attacks.'' The words were <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>'s but if you close your eyes and let your mind drift back to 1980 they might just as well have been <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s.
