<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ladies and gentlemen, sharpen your scalpels. The show that dares to comment on <PERSON> Patti </PERSON> <PERSON> LuPone </PERSON>'s diction, <PERSON> Madonna </PERSON>'s acting ability, <PERSON> Nell </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>'s figure and <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Brightman </PERSON>'s overbite has returned with malice and entertainment for all `` Forbidden Broadway 1988,'' which arrived Thursday at off-Broadway's Theater East, is the latest edition of <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> <PERSON> Alessandrini </PERSON>'s vest-pocket musical revues that mercilessly spoof the Broadway theater. And it's the best version of the show yet. In more than 25 musical sketches, a hard-working company of four, plus pianist <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Fortenberry </PERSON>, takes aim at some of Broadway's biggest hits including `` <LOCATION> Les </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Miserables </LOCATION>,'' `` The Phantom of the Opera,'' `` M. Butterfly,'' `` Speed-the-Plow,'' `` Anything Goes'' and `` Into the Woods.'' They score a bull's - eye nearly <PERSON> Alessandrini </PERSON>, who devised the show and supplied the new lyrics as well as the direction, is a master at deflating bombast. Consider his blitz of `` Les Miserables'' _ a mock mini-musical that deflates the big Broadway blockbuster. It's not easy simulating <PERSON> Trevor </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>'s turntable staging, but <PERSON> Alessandrini </PERSON> comes up with credible and hilaroius copy of it here. But then he also supplies a chandelier for something called `` The Phantom of the Musical,'' a duet for a masked <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Webber </PERSON> and a buck-toothed Miss <PERSON> Brightman </PERSON>. The author is equally effective at lancing big-time personalities. There's a narcissistic Miss <PERSON> LuPone </PERSON> mushmouthing a Cole Porter-style ditty called `` I Get a Kick Out of Me.'' Or an exasperated <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Mamet </PERSON