<FIRST>r i PM-Sweden-Immigration     09-16 0905</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sweden-Immigration,0934</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farming Town Resists Immigrants, Raising Questions Of Racism</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SJOBO, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's heartland is challenging <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>'s generous refugee policy, raising fears that latent racism may be bubbling to the surface. It's happening in <LOCATION> Sjobo </LOCATION>, a small southern farming town where the tallest building is three stories high, downtown is one street, and everyone knows just about everybody else. The 15,000 citizens of the town and the surrounding district are holding a referendum Sunday on whether to accept about 30 refugees. It is a local issue, but the question is drawing national attention and is dominating the final weeks of the campaign for the parliamentary election on the same day. Government figures say that from 1983 to 1987, 62,600 people sought political asylum in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, a country of 8.4 million people, making it the highest per capita rate in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Last year 245 of <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>'s 284 municipal districts took in 18,000 newcomers as the government tried to spread them outside <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION> and other cities where housing is scarce. When the request came to <LOCATION> Sjobo </LOCATION>, the town council balked. It voted last autumn by 25-24 to put the question to a popular vote. Residents say the issue has split families, friends and even the town's only church. Distrust and anger stop people from talking about it any more, and a sullenness has fallen on the town. `` A lot of people are very ashamed. It's terrible,'' said <PERSON> Madeleine </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramel </PERSON>, head of the local <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welfare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. `` The town has changed.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Ramel </PERSON> said the fight in Sjobo may spread to other communities that have been reluctant to take in refugees but that have been too afraid of public scorn to refuse. `` It is dangerous to ignore signals, and what is happening in <LOCATION> Sjobo </LOCATION> is one of the signals,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Ramel </PERSON>. The immigration department has said <PERSON> Sjobo </PERSON> could have a say in which immigrants would be sent. The decision has been postponed until after the referendum. An influx of immigrants from <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> has spawned a right-wing backlash in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> and other European countries, but that has not happened in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>. `` A lot of Swedes have a negative attitude toward immigrants. It is normally surpressed, but having a referendum is bringing it to the surface,'' said <PERSON> Anders </PERSON> <PERSON> Sonnerstedt </PERSON>, a political scientist at nearby <ORGANIZATION> Lund </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` Swedish people are afraid to speak about the refugee question today, because anyone who speaks out is called a racist,'' said <PERSON> Per-Ingvar </PERSON> <PERSON> Magnusson </PERSON>, a fertilizer dealer who favors keeping the immigrants out. <PERSON> Magnusson </PERSON>, chairman of the Sjobo branch of the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, denied he is motivated by racism. He said the town lacks housing and jobs for its own young people who are moving away, and he professed astonishment at the attention the town has received. `` They make us out to be stupid, fools, farmers who live in isolation,'' he said in an interview. The town simply wants to take care of its own first, he said. Mrs. <PERSON> Ramel </PERSON>, whose welfare board would handle the immigrants if they came, dismissed <PERSON> Magnusson </PERSON>'s argument. `` It's a silly question. Why ca n't 15,000 people take care of 30 more people. I think they -LRB- the opponents -RRB- just do n't want foreigners here.'' The nay-sayers in <LOCATION> Sjobo </LOCATION> have been roundly condemned by national leaders, the media and the public. One waitress complained that a customer passing through asked rudely if the restaurant `` has racism on the menu.'' <PERSON> Magnusson </PERSON> said he gets hundreds of letters of support from other Swedes. Many of them `` do n't even dare to sign their names'' for fear of being branded as a racist. <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>'s few openly racist groups are dismissed as an insignificant fringe. But the fight in <LOCATION> Sjobo </LOCATION> involves farmers who represent <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>'s roots, and a political party with long and illustrious history. The issue was an embarrassment to the national <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> during its election campaign, and party leader <PERSON> Olof </PERSON> <PERSON> Johansson </PERSON> threatened to expel the Sjobo members. `` They have made their last mistake in the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said in a television interview. The center-right party governs the local council in a coalition with the <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. On the national level, it is in the opposition against the governing <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> party. Set serenely among woodlands and wheatfields, <PERSON> Sjobo </PERSON> seems hardly the scene for a national confrontation. The town of 4,000 is laid out in neat rows of single-story homes with well-trimmed gardens. The <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has said the state would pay for housing and educating the immigrants. But <PERSON> Magnusson </PERSON> said the problem goes deeper. He said the government must curb an unchecked flood of immigrants. <PERSON> Magnusson </PERSON> cited police reports that more than half the refugees seeking to live in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> destroy their passports on their way here to make it difficult to deport them. Police say as many as 25,000 people may be in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> under false identities and that as many as 15 wanted terrorists move here every year. Among them were a Palestinian who was killed by a car bomb in <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> in July, and a wanted terrorist from the <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> who was arrested in August by Dutch police while traveling through the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. `` There are terrorists, drug dealers and criminals coming in,'' said <PERSON> Magnusson </PERSON>. `` If the government had more control of handling refugees, there would be no need for a vote in <LOCATION> Sjobo </LOCATION>.''
