<HEAD>British Tourist Rides Out Storm In Rental Car, Reading Horror
Story</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hurricane Gilbert</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANCUN, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowden </PERSON> of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> came to this <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> resort to get a tan. He ended up spending a dark day in a rented car, reading a horror story as he rode out <PERSON> Hurricane </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>, the worst storm on record. `` There was a lot of corrugated material flying about all over the place,'' said <PERSON> Bowden </PERSON>, 35. `` It was like being in an aircraft in turbulence. You felt the wind was going to lift you away.'' Other tourists crammed into <LOCATION> Cancun </LOCATION>'s hotels and shelters were becoming impatient by Thursday, the day after <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> blasted the <LOCATION> Yucatan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> with 160-mph winds and driving rain. Food was in short supply, power was still out, the airport was closed and roads out of the city nearly impassable. `` Hysterical,'' one hotel receptionist said of the stranded vacationers. About 6,000 tourists were trapped in <LOCATION> Cancun </LOCATION> when this normally idyllic resort of sandy beaches and warm, clear waters turned into a fury of waves and wind in the predawn hours Wednesday. <PERSON> Bowden </PERSON> drove into <LOCATION> Cancun </LOCATION> Tuesday, only hours before the storm hit. By then, tourists at the beachfront resorts were being moved into shelters and hotels in the old part of the city, about six miles away. As the hurricane neared, <PERSON> Bowden </PERSON> also sought refuge in the city, but was turned away by hotels already jammed with guests from the luxury resorts. As <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> roared into <LOCATION> Cancun </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bowden </PERSON> said he curled up in his car with a book, a horror story involving a magic carpet. `` I got sick of it. If I'd had some postcards I would have written them to send to people, but I did not have any,'' he said. <PERSON> Bowden </PERSON> said he watched as airborne debris zipped past his car. But even worse was the sound of two support lines of a radio transmission tower twanging `` like a badly tuned guitar'' in the wind. Shortly after dawn, the storm still raging, he said left the car, looking for some place to get a cup of coffee. Unsuccessful, he returned to the vehicle. About 150 tourists who were given refuge at city hall had nothing but milk and cookies to eat. `` I think everyone's nerves are starting to get shot now,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Camuccio </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, who had arrived in <LOCATION> Cancun </LOCATION> Sunday. `` Everyone is going to the same bathroom,'' he said. `` There is no water or electricity. They -LRB- the toilets -RRB- do n't flush or anything. Everybody wants to get out.'' Some tourists said they were given virtually no warning that a dangerous storm was on the way. <PERSON> Maggie </PERSON> <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Petaluma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, said she had just gotten dressed to go out for the evening Tuesday when there was a knock her hotel room door and a voice said: `` You're being evacuated.'' `` I started laughing thinking they were joking,'' she said. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Effingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, who speaks no Spanish, said the language barrier added to the confusion. He and his wife, <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON>, were in <LOCATION> Cancun </LOCATION> to celebrate their fifth wedding anniversary. <PERSON> Nabil </PERSON> <PERSON> Nachawati </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, said his two children, ages 3 and 5, took the storm well. When the sky began to darken, the two children curled up and went to sleep.
