<FIRST>r i PM-Peru-Inflation     09-16 0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Peru-Inflation,0800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peruvians Buy Hard Goods as Currency Loses Value</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With their currency losing ground rapidly in a spiraling inflation, Peruvians are buying up refrigerators and other durable goods not likely to lose value as fast as their paper money, the inti. After two years of prosperity, Peruvians are seeing an economic turnaround that is fueling the fastest increase in consumer prices ever seen here. Independent economists conservatively estimate that inflation will pass 500 percent this year. Two years ago inflation was 63 percent. `` The country is shipwrecked in a sea of paper money,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirinos </PERSON>, an independent. `` This is a horrifying perspective and never known before in our history.'' Consumer prices shot up 30.9 percent in July alone. Peruvians are trying to adjust. They say they eat less, work more and worry a lot. `` Now I have to buy less chicken. I use it first for broth and then stew. It's the only way,'' said housewife <PERSON> Carmen </PERSON> <PERSON> Alegre </PERSON>, while shopping in <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>'s working-class La <LOCATION> Aurora </LOCATION> market. Nearby, tennis shoes costing 500 intis early last year were selling for 3,000 intis, equivalent to about $ 25 or half the minimum monthly wage. Cigarettes, often sold singly because many Peruvians can not afford entire packs, cost 10 intis each or seven times the January price. Analysts are now concerned that <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s inflation could boil into four-digit figures next year. The middle class has begun renting spare rooms, tutoring, knitting and sewing piece work and selling home-cooked food such as meat-filled `` empanadas'' in streetside stands to make ends meet. But <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s poor, the vast majority of the population, have been affected the hardest. `` The poorest paid people in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> are earning less money than at any time since records have been kept,'' The Andean Report, an economic monthly, said in July. An old man begging in the shadow of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>'s downtown government palace complained recently that inflation was making him poorer. `` This fills up fast but the intis are worth nothing,'' he said, jiggling the dirty plastic cup he waves to passers-by. <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Reyes </PERSON>, manager of an appliance store, said he telephones wholesalers every day to get revised prices for the television sets, stoves and toasters he sells. But business has been good, <PERSON> Reyes </PERSON> said, noting customers have pulled cash from bank accounts where the annual interest is frozen at 130 percent to buy durable goods, whose value very well could rise in an inflation. `` The only option a saver has with his money is spend it,'' said the news magazine <ORGANIZATION> Caretas </ORGANIZATION>. `` Those who do not have the ability to save will simply have to seek a second job.'' <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>, 42, a married accountant with three children, said he recently began moonlighting as a curbside money trader on `` Wall Street,'' the name given by Peruvians to <PERSON> Jiron </PERSON> <PERSON> Ocona </PERSON>, a narrow downtown street where thousands of people every day now buy dollars as a hedge against inflation. He said many of his competitors are also professionals seeking to supplement inflation-pinched incomes with the small but quick profits offered by the dollar trade. Analysts say <PERSON> Jiron </PERSON> <PERSON> Ocona </PERSON> is also a financial barometer, and the recent stampede for dollars reflects Peruvians' waning confidence in the government's ability to improve economic conditions. In a recent survey, Peruvians rated the economy as the No. 1 problem, replacing a vicious leftist insurgency that was ranked first a year ago. President <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> imposed a ceiling on foreign debt payments on taking office three years ago and then used the money owed creditors abroad to finance a consumption-based economic reactivation that pulled <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> from its worst depression of the century. But heavy government spending with an expected deficit of at least 12 percent and a growing shortage of dollar reserves to subsidize imports have plunged the nation into recession this year. Manufacturing has fallen sharply, while speculation in consumer and industrial goods is rampant. Prosperity reflected by well-stocked stores two years ago has now been replaced with repeated and prolonged shortages of medicines, auto parts and basic foods, such as milk and sugar. <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, a populist whose term ends in 1990, recently installed a `` war economy,'' aimed at holding down wage increases while allowing prices to rise. But economists maintain the measures are not sufficent and predict inflation will continue to soar. `` When inflation hits 500 percent, it could very easily get out of hand,'' said one leading independent economist, <PERSON> Alejandro </PERSON> <PERSON> Toledo </PERSON>. `` This is my biggest concern. There will be a very high social cost and <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> is not a stable country.''
