<HEAD>South Texas Braces For Hurricane Gilbert</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `By mid-afternoon ..., to UPDATE with late
evening position, weather report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserColor HRX3, LaserPhotos BRO1, HT6, AT5, WX40</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vacationers fled <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> beaches Thursday, property owners boarded up homes and businesses, and emergenc workers filled sandbags and readied shelters as powerful Hurricane <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> took aim at the southern tip of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Tens of thousands of schoolchildren from <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Corpus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Christi </LOCATION> were given an unexpected holiday so families would have time to evacuate, and northbound highways were jammed Thursday afternoon. By 11 p.m., the center of <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> was about 275 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION> and a torrential rain was falling. The storm, with maximum sustained winds of 120 mph, was expected to continue with a gradual turn toward the northwest expected later, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> reported. <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION> police said they were requesting residents to consider evacuating, but were not ordering them to leave. `` We've never evacuated the city and the point is, where are you going to move 100,000 people?'' said Sgt. Dean <PERSON> Poos </PERSON>. In the coastal resort of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Padre </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, about 25 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION>, the mayor ordered the 1,000 residents to leave by 4 p.m. `` We ca n't force them to leave, but it does n't make any sense to stay,'' said Mayor <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinkerton </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, adding that water and electricity would be turned off Thursday afternoon. `` It sounds facetious, but people can stay as long as we can fingerprint them so we can identify them later,'' he said. The town's government workers were packing up and moving to higher ground, at a hotel in <LOCATION> McAllen </LOCATION>, about 75 miles to the west. `` Guests are checking out in an orderly manner, boats and trailers are leaving the island,'' said <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Bushnell </PERSON>, spokesman for the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Padre </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> Visitor and <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>. On <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, City Manager <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON> recommended Thursday evening that residents start evacuating. `` We are dealing with people's lives therefore at 8 o'clock we are recommending evacuation of the island. We feel that we can not wait until the morning to make that decision,'' <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON> said, adding that roadblocks would be set up at midnight on Interstate 45 to limit access to the island. Even in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, north of the most likely landfall and about 50 miles inland, the threat of <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> had an effect. Residents who remembered the damage from 1983's Hurricane <PERSON> Alicia </PERSON> taped up windows, stockpiled food and water and removed tall billboards along freeways. While some Houstonians bought bottled water, tuna fish, canned fruits and bread, residents of the exclusive <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oaks </LOCATION> neighborhood stocked up on canned crab and lobster and jars of caviar to weather the storm in style. Promoters there even decided to postpone Saturday night's sold-out show featuring <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON>, <PERSON> Liza </PERSON> <PERSON> Minnelli </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sammy </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> until Oct. 9 Military aircraft from bases along the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> were flown inland to wait out the storm at places like <LOCATION> Midland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, ideal because it's `` high and dry,'' said airport spokeswoman <PERSON> Marcy </PERSON> <PERSON> Blauvelt </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION> was given a 27 percent probability of being the spot where <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> will hit land Friday, though a hurricane watch was in effect along the entire <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> coast as well as the northeastern Mexican coast from <LOCATION> Tampico </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> estimated maximum sustained winds at 120 mph and said some strengthening was likely with <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> headed out over the open waters of the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. The hurricane, spawned last week in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, caused at least 36 deaths in three island nations and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s Yucatan and left nearly one in four Jamaicans homeless. In <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION>, at least 30 emergency shelters were being set up, with the <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> boarded up and designated as the first to be used. `` We are getting some sandbags ready with some volunteers in case the agencies need them,'' said <PERSON> Timo </PERSON> <PERSON> Hinojosa </PERSON>, civil defense volunteer coordinator for <LOCATION> Cameron </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. A Greyhound-Trailways bus spokesman said the company was doubling its schedule of outbound buses to accommodate those fleeing the storm. In <LOCATION> Corpus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Christi </LOCATION>, about 170 miles up the coast, residents seemed more prepared for <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> than for previous storms, officials said. <LOCATION> Nueces </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Commissioner <PERSON> J.P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Luby </PERSON> said workers removed heavy objects from open areas, and many residents were stocking up on emergency items. Many grocery stores in <LOCATION> Corpus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Christi </LOCATION>, the largest city on the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, had run out of bottled drinking water and some canned food. Plywood was sold out in some places. <ORGANIZATION> Southwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> asked cellular phone customers in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> to try to keep the airwaves clear to allow emergency and relief workers plenty of communication space. The company loaned 100 cellular phone units to <ORGANIZATION> Corpus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christi </ORGANIZATION> officials and 100 more to cities in the Lower <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> McGeeney </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Southwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>. Two people in <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION> were arrested on charges of price-gouging, and Attorney General <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Mattox </PERSON> said he has a task force to prosecute people caught raising prices to take advantage of Texans preparing for <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>. `` They are doubling and tripling prices for the products. It is unconscionable for persons to take advantage of others who are in desperate need,'' he said. On Wednesday, Gov. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Clements </PERSON> issued an emergency proclamation allowing local authorities to temporarily suspend `` applicable rules, regulations and statutes to preserve the health, safety and welfare of the public,'' including such things as the direction of highways.
