<HEAD>Carnegie Hall Stage Adding Acoustic Screens</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Movable panels of sound-absorbing material should improve the sound of music from the stage of <LOCATION> Carnegie </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hall </LOCATION>, say officials of the famous concert hall. The beige, cloth-covered fiberglass panels were unveiled at a news conference Thursday as a response to complaints from some critics and musicians about acoustics since the hall's major renovation two years ago. The panels, in nine sections that can be carried on or off stage by stagehands, cost a total of $ 30,000, officials said. <PERSON> Isaac </PERSON> <PERSON> Stern </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Carnegie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hall </ORGANIZATION>, said the panels are designed to absorb mid-to-high-range sound. `` The result is that you can feel the wood quality of a great violin and of a piano and woodwinds,'' <PERSON> Stern </PERSON> said, adding he thinks orchestral blend also will be improved by the panels. `` The challenge was to provide a modest amount of absorption that would absorb only in a certain frequency range,'' said <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Carnegie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hall </ORGANIZATION> vice president and director of real estate planning and development.
