<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARWICK, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Black </PERSON> is n't one to shirk his responsibilites, but then he also did n't count on them entailing any heavy lifting. The lawyer, who earned the job of field driver by dint of being the town's most recently married man, refused to round up a stray 800-pound bull calf when called to perform his task. `` I said I was off duty,'' he joked Thursday. `` I consider the position of field driver to be a desk job.'' <PERSON> Black </PERSON> was married May 7, a few weeks before he was appointed to the post at Town Meeting according to a 200-year-old tradition in this central <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> town of 600 people. `` I suppose 200 years ago, when everybody knew something about cows and bulls, it made more sense,'' he said. He was called to the job Monday for the first time, when a calf was discovered in a back yard. `` I do n't know one end of a cow from another,'' he said. `` I was very lucky there was someone there who did.'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, the selectmen's chairman, and employees of <PERSON> Young </PERSON>'s lumber company corralled the calf <PERSON> Black </PERSON> said he was called only as a courtesy. `` Nobody really calls the field driver and expects him to chase a bull,'' he said. `` A couple of chickens I could handle, but that's it.''
