<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,860</SECOND>
<HEAD>Singapore Crackdown on Porkers Benefits U.S. Poultry Producers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The tiny island nation of <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> has turned into a prime market for American poultry, particularly cut up parts of chickens, an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> trade analyst says. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Kurz </PERSON> of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, until recently the agency's trade officer in <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, said the country's decision to eliminate pig farms is behind the poultry boom. `` In a drive for a cleaner environment, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> has increased the tempo in eliminating all pig farms,'' <PERSON> Kurz </PERSON> said. `` Since many <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> pig farms also have poultry operations, the number of poultry farms also has declined sharply.'' Consequently, poultry production has dropped, causing <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>'s poultry imports to rise to record levels. <PERSON> Kurz </PERSON>, who now is serving with the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> agency in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, writes about the <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> poultry boom in the October issue of Foreign Agriculture magazine. Imports of chicken parts were up 20 percent, with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> accounting for more than half, nearly 25,000 metric tons. That was about six times the level of imports from <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, the nearest rival. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>'s imports of frozen whole chickens dropped 14 percent last year, reflecting a local preference for live poultry imported from <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kurz </PERSON> said. Subsidized shipments of frozen whole chickens from the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> have held <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> competition to a minimum. `` However, export opportunities for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> suppliers may lie in the emerging market for breakfast meats, particularly turkey roll and <LOCATION> turkey </LOCATION> meat,'' <PERSON> Kurz </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> shipments of chilled and frozen ducks, geese, turkeys and guinea fowl also have increased and `` occupied a commanding position'' in the <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> market in 1987, he said. Is there a future for American poultry producers in <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, a country less than a fourth the size of <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and a population of 2.5 million? `` Everyone involved in this market, from breeders to retailers, believes that <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>'s poultry consumption _ especially chicken meat _ will rise, although prices appear to be headed upward,'' <PERSON> Kurz </PERSON> said. The price hikes and the conversion to a pig-free environment `` do not deter optimistic forecasts as more fast-food outlets and the restaurant trade boost the consumption of chicken,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Limited feed supplies could slow <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s ambitious drive to boost livestock and poultry production, an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report says The current five-year plan for increasing the output of meat 18 percent from 19.3 million metric tons in 1985 to 22.75 million metric tons by 1990 is meeting with some success, the report by the department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. `` The limiting factor in Chinese livestock and poultry production gains will be feed supplies,'' the report said. `` In turn, feed grain imports will be constrained in the next two to three years by <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s ability to earn sufficient foreign exchange for these purchases.'' <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is an important but sometimes erratic market for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farmers, and the livestock sector is watched closely for signs that more grain and feed sales may be developing. One of the problems cited in the report, which was included in the October issue of Foreign Agriculture magazine, is this year's rise in world grain prices, caused by tighter supplies resulting primarily from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drought `` Should world commodity prices remain high, the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government is likely to squeeze exports of corn and soybeans out of the domestic market in order to earn badly needed foreign exchange,'' the report said. In 1985-86, it said, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> exported more than 6 million tons of corn from its northern provinces while importing 400,000 tons into the south. `` As in the past, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> will continue to export soybeans for foreign exchange and barter with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S.S.R. </ORGANIZATION> and other <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> countries,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is seeking permission from the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> to field-test a genetically engineered bacterium to control a serious disease of wheat. Officials said Thursday that the test, if approved by <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>, would begin next month on a 1.5-acre site at <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unversity </ORGANIZATION>'s agriculture facility near <LOCATION> Pullman </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash </LOCATION> The test would be conducted by <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and the university. The test would involve a USDA-discovered strain of a bacterium, pseudomonas, which controls the wheat disease called `` take all.'' The bacterium was genetically altered by <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION> so it can be tracked easily in the field. `` Before the bacterium can be turned into a commercial product for use by farmers to control take all, we need to know exactly what happens when it is released into a field,'' said <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> said that among other things, scientists need to know whether the bacterium spreads into surrounding plants or water, or if it survives into the following season. <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> and his colleagues at the agency's Root Disease and <ORGANIZATION> Biological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pullman </LOCATION> discovered the bacterium strain and conducted seven years of tests to prove its ability to control the wheat disease, the department said.
