<HEAD>Ecologists Say `Let It Burn' Policy Is Sound</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 You do n't preserve a forest by putting out all fires, ecologists observe in defending the `` let it burn'' policy of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. The forest will keep changing as plant and animal species kept down by periodic natural fires establish themselves, and, `` You're going to culminate in a few species that can out-compete the others,'' said <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Roughgarden </PERSON>, professor of biological sciences at <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> `` It must be understood that nothing is preserved by stopping burning,'' said <PERSON> Roughgarden </PERSON>, who was a member of a panel for reporters organized by the American Association for the Advancement of Science on Thursday. The panel was trying to call attention to ecology, the science that studies the relationships of organisms with their environments. Today's issue of Science, the weekly scientific journal of the association, has a special section on the subject. The word `` ecology'' is not properly a synonym for `` environment,'' <PERSON> Roughgarden </PERSON> observed at one point: `` It is not something you should be for or against. It is simply there.'' Others on the panel _ who were quick to point out they were not specialists in fire ecology _ said government agencies should not return to the days of trying to put out all fires and the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> was widely using its anti-fire cartoon symbol of Smoky the Bear. However, they said revisions in the `` let it burn'' policy might be desirable in light of the burning of half of <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> this summer. `` A backlash returning us to Smoky the Bear would be a larger disaster than the fires,'' said <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilbur </PERSON>, professor of zoology at <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` The worst possible thing that could happen would be to go back to a total fire-suppression policy,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON>, a research ecologist at <ORGANIZATION> Oak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ridge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>. Fire suppression brings `` reduced landscape diversity, which can cause the transmission of disturbances such as fire, or a pest,'' said <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON>. The loss of diversity is `` a brand-new problem ... a new area of research.'' `` There remains a good ecological basis for the plan of controlled burning'' that government agencies follow, said <PERSON> Roughgarden </PERSON>. `` Without fire you simply obtain an entirely different vegetation type.'' Though the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> has been using controlled burning in some parks, it had not been used in <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>.
