<HEAD>Movement Toward Round-Table Talks: New Ball Game for Poland</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The carefully choreographed steps by the government and opposition toward a broad-based national dialogue represent the most significant opening in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s political impasse since the 1981 martial law crackdown. But serious obstacles remain before any ompromise can be reached that would bridge the chasm dividing Polish authorities from the East bloc's largest and best-organized opposition movement. After their second working meeting in 16 days Thursday, Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and Interior Minister Gen. <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> indicated that efforts toward round-table talks _ broad-based discussions on <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s future _ were on track. Another meeting today involves for the first time other Solidarity representatives and members of the official trade union alliance OPZZ. Opposition activists appeared satisfied that authorities are willing in principle to re-legalize Solidarity in a form yet to be negotiated. `` I would say that both sides are not terribly far apart as far as basic things are concerned,'' said pro-Solidarity journalist <PERSON> Krzysztof </PERSON> <PERSON> Sliwinski </PERSON>. What remains to be seen, he said, is how different the new Solidarity would be from the mass social movement of 1980-81. <PERSON> Ludwig </PERSON> <PERSON> Krasucki </PERSON>, an editor of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> monthly <PERSON> Nowe </PERSON> <PERSON> Drogi </PERSON>, said in an interview there was a better than 50 percent chance that union pluralism would be allowed. `` It can not be easy,'' he said. `` It needs some time. And then I think we will open a process'' of negotiation. The government overtures after seven years of deadlock comes amid signs that communist authorities are psychologically prepared to accept the permanent existence of an organized political opposition. Some officially published commentaries have even gone so far as to praise the effects of an active opposition movement. `` States having a strong political opposition keep developing, while the socialist states are sinking in crisis,'' said one particularly startling commentary in the officially published weekly Odrozenie. After struggling without marked success to govern alone, the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> -LRB- </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- Party led by Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> is hoping through round-table talks with <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> to tap the energy of the opposition that it crushed in 1981. But there is a catch: whatever formula is devised, it must somehow guarantee that the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> keeps the dominant role. Proposals have been floated in the press, such as reserving a significant minority of parliament seats for the opposition, or creating a new upper chamber of parliament with limited powers which would not have a guaranteed majority of communist deputies. But it is highly uncertain whether <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s skeptical and pragmatic opposition would ever accept anything that smacked of tokenism or being co-opted by the system. <PERSON> Krasucki </PERSON> said the majority of party membership is ready for a `` big compromise'' in political reform, and that he thought <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> would bring about the changes. But a grand old man of the Polish opposition movement, Socialist <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jozef </PERSON> <PERSON> Lipski </PERSON>, said he was skeptical of any speedy promises of reform. `` The direction of changes will get deeper, that's for sure,'' he said. `` But it will take much more time.'' The government's decision to enter into talks, taken in the midst of last month's strikes and signs that <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s downward economic spiral is worsening, gives the appearance of a country coming full circle. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> was also in dire economic straits in 1980 when strikes lifted the then unknown <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> into the role of spokesman for an entire society's grievances. A tide of social unrest forced authorities then to deal with <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, but over the next 15 -LCB- months it was confrontation, not acceptance that characterized government actions toward the union. The December 1981 martial law crackdown was merely the final blow. Outlawing Solidarity and detaining thousands of its supporters only exacerbated the government's problems. The economy continued to falter and the government had little domestic support to draw upon when mounting foreign debt forced it into unpopular austerity measures. Solidarity in turn has been frustrated by its outlaw status, which has hampered its effectiveness as a trade union by subjecting members to legal reprisals and preventing them from working openly to organize factories. Both sides, tired and fed up with the status quo, would like to see a change. Possible outlines of a compromise emerged in the first interview with <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> published in the official Polish press since the martial law crackdown. Since authorities will not totally abandon the official trade unions set up after Solidarity, a major question is how both Solidarity and those unions can exist in the same workplaces. Speaking to the monthly <PERSON> Konfrontacje </PERSON>, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> cited the example of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, where multiple unions co-exist in a single factory and negotiate jointly with management through elected workers' councils
