<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Textile-state lawmakers, racing to gain approval of their embattled import-limiting bill before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> adjourns, confess anxiety over fresh delays being threatened in the House. `` They could outdistance us, we just do n't have that much time in this Congress,'' Sen. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.C. </LOCATION>, said Thursday after the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approved the bill 59-36 in a rerun of action it took last week. Designed to protect American industry from foreign competition, the bill won approval last week only to remain bottled up in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> when opponents seized on a technicality to delay it. Thursday's vote freed the bill from that snarl and sent it to the House. The bill would freeze textile and apparel imports at 1987 levels and limit growth to 1 percent annually starting next year. It would hold nonrubber footwear imports to 1987 levels and ban further increases in foreign producers' share of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has been fighting over new import curbs for three years, with sponsors saying they are needed to save both American jobs and an industry that is vital to the nation's defense. Critics concede apparel companies have problems but say the textile industry is flourishing. Indeed, opponents credit stepped up competition from overseas with prodding the textile industry to modernize. They attribute a wave of layoffs since the early 1980s to increased automation. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> vetoed an earlier version of the bill in 1985, saying it would narrow consumer choices and cost more jobs than it would save. The current version is moving slowly forward amid threats of another presidential veto. `` The president's going to veto it, fortunately, and I hope that we have the votes to sustain the veto,'' Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON>, R-Ore., told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> `` America can not turn its back on the world. It's going to be part of it, and, frankly, I'd rather participate in it. Textile forces had hoped that the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> would give swift approval to the four changes that the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> made since the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passed the bill a year ago. But the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> voted Wednesday to negotiate the differences in a <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> conference committee. `` A conference just delays the time,'' <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON> complained to reporters Thursday after the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s action. The Ways and Means action Wednesday appeared to dash textile supporters' hopes that the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> changes would get a stamp of approval and a quick trip to the White House. But House Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, said it was not certain the measure would go to a conference committee. The president can prevent a bill from becoming law when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is not in session merely by not signing it. This is called a pocket veto. Textile forces are trying to avoid one, saying it would lower the political price paid by the administration with elections coming by keeping the spotlight off the issue. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> have set an adjournment target date of Oct. 5. Avoiding a pocket veto and forcing <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to actually use his veto pen also just could give textile forces a chance to try for an override and pass the measure into law over the president's objections The bill has not demonstrate