<HEAD>Credit-Repair Clinics Draw More Attention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Credit-repair companies, little known before the 1980s, have increasingly become the target of law enforcement agencies because of their deceptive practices, say federal officials. The companies promise to help remove derogatory information from individuals' credit files, and charge as much as $ 2,000 for the service. Ms. <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Noonan </PERSON>, an official in the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>'s bureau of consumer protection, told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee Thursday `` it appears that a substantial segment of the industry engages in deceptive advertising and sales practices.'' <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walton </PERSON>, inspector-deputy assistant director of the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>'s criminal investiative division, told the panel of a recent case involving <ORGANIZATION> Credit-Rite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Palmyra </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, which defrauded at least 9,000 consumers of $ 2.3 million in a credit-repair scheme in 15 states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>. The investigation resulted in three convictions with the founder-president, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, being sentenced to seven years in prison, <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, former director of franchising, receiving a prison sentence of 15 months, and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, credit-repair manager, receiving three years probation. The clinics take advantage of the law that gives consumers the right to challenge the information about them that credit bureaus have on file. This provision requires a credit bureau to verify the information upon request, generally within 30 days. If verification is not completed on time, the disputed data must be deleted. Under the law, individuals who feel their credit records have inaccuracies can go directly to a local credit bureau and ask that they be corrected. However, accurate derogatory information can remain as part of an individual's credit history for seven years or, in the case of a bankruptcy, for 10 years. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kurth </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureaus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a trade association representing over 1,200 consumer credit bureaus, said, `` The wrong being committed by credit clinics is the promise held out to intimidated consumers, that by some magic a credit clinic can accomplish things that the consumer can not accomplish and that false promises, rooted in half truths, will cost the consumer several hundred dollars or more. `` The illness of a poor credit history can only be cured by time and careful reconstruction of a consumer's payment history with creditors in the future,'' <PERSON> Kurth </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Banking consumer affairs subcommittee. The subcommittee is considering legislation, introduced by Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON>, D-Ill., which would restrict the practices of credit-repair clinics
