 As vice presidential candidate <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> took the stage carrying <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' message for the South, the event resembled a reunion for Democrats who once worked together and won the White House. The <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> senator was flanked by <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>'s top elected officials _ Gov. <PERSON> Ned </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> McWherter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sens </PERSON>. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasser </PERSON>. The audience was filled with cheering local sheriffs, school board members and party activists. `` I know what's happened the last two presidential elections,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Shelby </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> fund-raiser Thursday night. `` You've seen some of our Democratic friends go into that voting booth, pull that curtain, and vote for <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. `` Now, we understand that, and we respect that,'' he said, pausing before the punch line: `` But now we're saying, ` Democrats who voted for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, welcome home, welcome back to our party.''' The crowd roared. The <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign knows that <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> can repeat that scene in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION>, and it can only hope that the effort will help score a win on Nov. 8 for the Democratic ticket. <PERSON> Tad </PERSON> <PERSON> Devine </PERSON>, who watches the polls and directs the vice presidential campaign from Dukakis-Bentsen headquarters in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, says <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> is `` an effective tool'' for convincing conservative Democrats they can vote for the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor. `` I expect that he'll continue to sort of ` credential' Governor <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> before these audiences,'' <PERSON> Devine </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. `` Everywhere he's been so far, he's been very well received in terms of the political impact,'' including extensive coverage and interviews with the local press. But there are doubts outside the campaign. `` ` Credentialing' is an academic approach to saying the fella ca n't stand on his own two feet,'' said <PERSON> Claibourne </PERSON> <PERSON> Darden </PERSON>, an Atlanta-based pollster and consultant whose clients include Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, D-Ga. `` It's like getting a Ph.D. because you ca n't get a job. While it's smart for <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> to focus on the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> _ `` You fish where the fish bite,'' he said _ the vice presidential candidate can only open the door for the presidential candidate to walk through. `` The question is, how capable is <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> at walking through these doors in the South? The answer so far is not so good,'' <PERSON> Darden </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON>, the Dukakis-Bentsen campaign's Southern regional director, said the evidence was to the contrary. In the <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> hotel ballroom, he pointed out local officials who would n't be caught near the two previous Democratic tickets `` They call them leaders, but really they tend to follow the voters,'' he said. `` They're still moving toward the ticket. They're with the ticket.'' But <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON> acknowledged that <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s easy popularity with Southern Democrats who voted for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was n't enough. `` You're definitely going to see <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> follow up'' with more Southern trips himself, he said, citing the governor's previous Southern swings. `` I do n't think he -LRB- <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> -RRB- closes the deal.'' <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON> declined to say which Southern states the Democrats believe they are capable of winning but <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s schedule this week follows the scenario the campaign acknowledges privately. Besides his native <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, which is a neck-and-neck battle, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> was hunting for votes in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. He was in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> just last weekend. <PERSON> Lance </PERSON> <PERSON> Tarrance </PERSON>, a Houston-based political consultant for the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION>, said <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> also were states where <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> helps the Democratic ticket. `` But let's be frank _ it's <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>,'' with their 47 and 29 electoral votes, the Democrats were after, <ORGANIZATION> Tarrance </ORGANIZATION> said. And although <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> had a lot of pride tied up in the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> race, `` <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> is the one that really hurts the Republicans if it goes to the Democrats,'' he said. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> helped in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> in areas where <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was weak, he said. The deep South, especially states such as <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, was very unlikely to produce a win for the Democrats. `` The South because of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> presidency is very strong for <PERSON> Bush </PERS