<HEAD>President Hosts `Simple, 14-Course Supper' For Lawmakers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd, 24 grafs to correct punctuation</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> said, it was just `` a simple, 14-course picnic supper'' as President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> played host for a congressional barbecue laced with tart lyrics by a troupe of former <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> aides. <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, the Democrat from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state who is <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> majority leader, traded pleasantries with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> at the conclusion of the annual event on the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> lawn Thursday, which will be the last for the president and first lady <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. As lawmakers and administration officials dined on food from four tents _ giving them their choice of seafood, Cajun, Western or Mexican cuisine _ entertainnment was provided by the Capitol Steps, a group formed six years ago at a Capitol Christmas party. The Reagans joined in the applause as the Steps aimed their satire both at the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration and Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. The president laughed heartily, for instance, as a member of the troupe impersonating the Republican presidential nominee, who has been charting an increasingly independent course, sang: `` I sorta ... kinda ... remotely ... `` Distantly wan na be like you.'' In another skit, a singer representing <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> sang to the tune of `` September Song'': `` Try to remember `` That date in September `` The day <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> `` Attacked <LOCATION> Pearl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>.'' The audience erupted in laughter at the reference to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s speech at an American Legion convention in <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION> on Sept. 7, in which he said that that day, instead of Dec. 7, was the anniversary of the attack that plunged the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> into World War II Democratic nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> did not get off scot free, either, as the singers hymned a presidential campaign pitting the `` Duke of Dullness'' against `` Sir <PERSON> George </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> even burst into laughter at what was probably the harshest satire of the evening, one in which he was represented as musing upon his place in history and intoning: `` Well ... `` Do n't know much about history `` Do n't know much about geography `` Do n't know much about World War II `` Do n't know much about who fought who `` But I know it followed World War I `` If we only fought in the wars we won `` What a wonderful world this would be.'' In his concluding remarks, the president said, `` I want to thank the Capitol Steps for showing such _ mercy. Now you're all under arrest.'' Noting that it would be the last such affair he would host, the president said, `` After 6 o'clock, we all take off the cleats and come together as friends and colleagues.'' <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> told the president, `` Unanimously, we wish you and Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> thanks, first of all for your many courtesies, and secondly, as you go in, not to a retirement but a different part of your life in which I know you'll be concerned as you have been for the future of this country and for its role in the world, the best of every happiness, success and satisfaction.''
