<HEAD>Reagan Expected To Sign Spy Satellite Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is expected to sign a bill to modernize the nation's spy satellite network as part of intelligence agency activities over the coming year,. Precise provisions of the measure, which was approved by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday, have not been revealed. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approved by voice vote a compromise measure which the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> had passed a day earlier. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> initiated the major modernization program for electronic spying after concluding that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> photo and eavesdropping satellites are growing outmoded. The nation's spy capabilities in space have not been substantially updated in a decade. In reviewing how well the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could verify Soviet compliance with the new Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces, or INF, treaty, the panel found that monitoring technology would be inadequate if the superpowers reach later agreement on deep cuts in long-range nuclear weapons. A compromise was reached with the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration on the amount of money needed for the program, but it was uncertain whether <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will appropriate the funds. That issue is tied up in a dispute over a separate Pentagon appropriations bill. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> opposes the initiative, saying it has been too hastily conceived and would not substantially enhance <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> treaty-monitoring ability. The exact amounts for the spy satellite program and the overall intelligence budget are secret, but total spending on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence programs reportedly is approximately $ 25 billion. Nearly all of the money is hidden in the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s budget. Among other provisions in the intelligence bill: _ Stronger language prohibiting the government from aiding <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Contra rebels unless specifically authorized by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> The issue became controversial during the Iran-Contra affair when the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration insisted prohibitions on intelligence agencies aiding the rebels did not extend to the president's <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> staff. The new legislation bars any `` entity'' of the government from unauthoried aid to the Contras, which would include the <ORGANIZATION> NSC </ORGANIZATION>. _ A requirement that the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> report to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> about the activities of the agency's internal inspector general, who investigates allegations of wrongdoing The provision also would require the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> director to tell congressional overseers any time he bars the inspector general from undertaking a specific investigation. The only dollar amounts mentioned in the unclassified version of the intelligence bill were a $ 23.7 million authorization for the 244-member intelligence community staff, which serves the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> director in his role of coordinator of all government intelligence activities; $ 15.1 million for <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> counterintelligence activities in keeping tabs on Soviet inspectors at <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> weapons sites under the INF treaty; and $ 144.5 million for the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>'s retirement and disability fund.
