<HEAD>Evacuees Asked To Bring Food, Leave Beer, Firearms Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 They were told to bring their own food, drinks and blankets, but warned to leave their pets, booze and guns at home. And they did. As Hurricane <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>, perhaps the most-feared storm of its kind, approached the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> coast, residents fled their homes, taking bedrolls and food supplies to <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> shelters on higher ground. In this southernmost <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> city, where the eye of <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> was predicted to pass sometime this evening, 750 people filled the civic auditorium to its capacity within four hours, while hundreds of others crowded into schools. For some, their flight to the shelters was reminiscent of Hurricane Beulah, which struck <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION> in 1980 and Hurricane Allen, which landed north of <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION> the same year. `` We brought food, water, some milk, but my husband forgot the stereo and all our medicine, but I think we will be all right,'' said 77-year-old <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON>, a diabetic in a wheelchair. Families staked out perimeters on the floor of the civic center, placing blankets, sheets and pillows on the floor next to bags of food and ice chests filled with meats and soft drinks. Some children brought their plastic toys and some brought their teddy bears while others turned on their small radios and tuned in to news of the storm. `` Most of the people who come here or to other shelters in the -LRB- <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION> -RRB- <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> are those who do n't have transportation to go north,'' said <PERSON> Ersel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lantz </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> effort at the civic center. `` We have all kinds of people here, from those that need Pampers, to those that need wheelchairs,'' he said. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON>, 19, said he boarded up the home of mother and grandparents in nearby <LOCATION> Olmito </LOCATION> and drove them to the civic center. `` We just decided this was the best place to be because of all the predictions of damage it could cause,'' <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Elena </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON>, 34, brought her children to the shelter because she feared staying in her second-story apartment. `` We know that there might be an emergency and we do n't have a car and we knew we could come here where there are a lot of people and if something happened, we knew we could get something if we needed it,'' Ms. <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Ricky </PERSON> <PERSON> Saldierna </PERSON>, 7, said would rather be at home. `` I think this hurricane is very bad because it could hurt somebody, especially some kids like me,'' he said. `` I wish we were in school now and I wish we were back in our own house.''
