<FIRST>r i PM-Singapore     09-16 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Singapore,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Losing Candidates Get Seats In Parliament</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Only one opposition candidate was elected earlier this month, but two of the losers will be appointed to join him in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> under a controversial measure designed to ensure opposing voices are heard. The measure, whereby the two members will get `` non-constituency'' seats, was introduced before the last polls in 1984 by amending the constitution to create limited opposition, after the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> won every seat in the four previous general elections. The <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> has been in power since 1959 under Prime Minister <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuan </PERSON> <PERSON> Yew </PERSON>. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said that in two years of Cabinet discussion such alternatives as proportional representation and a second chamber in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> were considered and rejected as unsuitable for this island republic of 2.6 million people. Opposition politicians condemned the new measure as a means of perpetuating <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> rule. <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> See </PERSON> <PERSON> Tong </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Singapore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> was the only opposition candidate to win at the polls on Sept. 3. The <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> took 80 of 81 seats _ 11 of them unopposed _ and 64.6 percent of the valid votes cast. <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON>, who was first elected in 1984, repeated his rejection of non-constituency seats Sunday. According to the measure, the seats are offered to the three best performers among the opposition losers. If one or two opposition candidates manage to win at the polls, as <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> did, extra seats are added up to a total of three. Those appointed must have polled at least 15 percent of the vote in their constituencies and must belong to a political party. They enjoy most of the rights and privileges of the other 81 <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> members and can speak on any issue. But they can not vote on no-confidence motions, proposals to amend the constitution or bills to supply funds to the government or tax money from the people. They represent no constituency. Opposition parties rejected the one appointment offered after the 1984 election when <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> and Workers' Party leader <PERSON> J.B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jeyaretnam </PERSON> were voted into Parliament. <PERSON> Jeyaretnam </PERSON> denounced the measure then as `` a ruse to try to keep the electorate thinking of the <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> as the only government, providing for everything, including opposition MPs.'' <PERSON> Jeyaretnam </PERSON> still heads the Workers' Party but was ousted from <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and disqualified for five years from 1986 for allegedly falsifying party records. After a week of heated intra-party debate, <PERSON> Jeyaretnam </PERSON> announced Saturday that two of its losers would accept the offer to enter Parliament. If he had said no, seats would have been offered to the next two highest-polling losers. <PERSON> Jeyaretnam </PERSON> said his party remained opposed to the concept of non-constituency seats and its acceptance of them should not `` be regarded as a precedent for the party's decision in future cases.'' The Workers' Party will be represented by lawyer <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Seow </PERSON> and a physician, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Siew </PERSON> <PERSON> Choh </PERSON>. <PERSON> Seow </PERSON>, 59, a former solicitor general and president of the <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, is a newcomer to party politics and was widely expected to run as an independent. He was released on July 16 after 72 days in jail under the country's Internal Security Act, which permits detention without trial. The government alleged that <PERSON> Seow </PERSON> conspired with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomats to increase the parliamentary opposition to the government. However, he has since been accused of income tax evasion and faces trial in December. If convicted, <PERSON> Seow </PERSON> would lose his <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> seat.
</TEXT>
