<HEAD>New Warhol Jewel Cache Discovered in Hidden File Drawers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A year-and-a-half after his death, <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> has sprung another surprise: hundreds of diamonds, sapphires and other jewelry worth $ 1.2 million and found hidden in a file cabinet. Curators uncovered the secret cache at the artist's <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> townhouse, <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION>'s announced Thursday. The value of the jewelry was put at $ 1.2 million. But as last spring's auction proved, anything associated with <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> is likely to sell for far more than its book value. <PERSON> Sotheby </PERSON>'s said two curators were moving file cabinets at the townhouse in June when they discovered the jewels stashed in false-bottom drawers. The find included hundreds of diamonds, dozens of sapphires and a 300-carat emerald, <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION>'s said. There also were 96 watches by such makers as Patek <PERSON> Philippe </PERSON>, <PERSON> Rolex </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Cartier </ORGANIZATION>. The jewelry will be auctioned Dec. 4, with proceeds going to the <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> Foundation. At the earlier auction, jewelry that had been valued at approximately $ 500,000 brought in $ 1.9 million as a frenzy of Warholmania sent prices of his art and belongings soaring. The flat file cabinets with the jewels had been used by <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> to store unframed drawings and prints. They had been examined before last spring's auction, but no one noticed the hollow bottoms, <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION>'s spokesman <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Weigman </PERSON> said. The curators discovered the false bottoms only after they removed the bottom drawers to lighten the cabinets before moving them, he said. <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> died in February 1987 at age 58.
