<TEXT>
 More than 1,500 animals at the <PERSON> Gladys </PERSON> <PERSON> Porter </PERSON> <PERSON> Zoo </PERSON> were included in the preparations for Hurricane <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>. `` All the animals will have some kind of shelter. Tender birds or those capable of flight in high wind are locked up first,'' General Curator <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Stones </PERSON> said Thursday. `` We try to wait until the last minute to do this because it puts a lot of stress on the birds and we do n't want to have them in there too long or longer than we have to.'' Workers also will place extra hay and feed in zoo buildings, check generators and secure equipment from high winds. The zoo was already prepared for a hurricane, with a year-round cache of supplies, including flashlights, batteries, boots, lumber, food, water and generators, said Stones.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hurricane <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> has similarities to <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, which had winds up to 200 mph but diminished before it reached the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> coastline in 1980, meteorologists say. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> caused heavy flooding and two deaths, but its assault on <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> in August 1980 was far less serious than had been feared. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> _ one of the most powerful hurricanes then on record _ slammed across the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> with lethal force and built to Category 5 strength. <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> also built to the same strength before weakening as it passed over <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Yucatan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, with a diameter of more than 600 miles, rapidly built in intensity and crossed the gulf on Aug. 7 with winds near 200 mph. It sent hundreds of thousands of people on an exodus from the coast but its rush toward land suddenly stalled as a high-pressure ridge fended it off. By the time <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> crashed into the coast early Aug. 10, its winds had diminished to around 100 mph and it was classified as a Category 3 hurricane. At least 67 people were reported killed in <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> after <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> raced over the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> island of <LOCATION> Hispaniola </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> employees were sent home for the weekend to secure their homes, get supplies or leave the area as Hurricane <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> approached the coast. Normally, the space center is closed to visitors only on Christmas Day. But it shut down at noon Thursday and employees were told they did n't have to return until normal work times Monday, spokesman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartsfield </PERSON> said. At the space center, about 25 miles from the coast, there are 3,382 civil employees and 5,665 workers from companies contracting with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. A core group will remain throughout the weekend at <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>, the strongest building at the center and the place where shuttle flights are controlled, <ORGANIZATION> Hartsfield </ORGANIZATION> said. Mission Control has concrete walls and no windows. `` If the storm hurts that -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, we're really in trouble,'' he said. If the space center withstands substantial damage, <ORGANIZATION> Hartsfield </ORGANIZATION> said the expected launch of the first post-Challenger flight at <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaveral </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, would n't be affected. But <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> officials on Wednesday decided not to set an exact date for the long-waited launch of Discovery because of the storm.
