<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> today hailed the formation of a new political party organized by her supporters but said the move must not divide democratic forces into `` permanent hostile camps.'' Formation of the new party is the latest step in a realignment of forces which ousted leader <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> in February 1986 and swept Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> into power. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> made her remarks in a speech to the opening session of the first national convention of the new party, the `` Struggle of the Democratic Filipino.'' Rep. <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitra </PERSON>, speaker of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION>, was elected president of the party, which organizers hope will bring together pro-government forces under a single banner and serve as the president's own party. But some pro-Aquino politicians have attacked the new party as a bid by the president's relatives and others to consolidate their own power in advance of the 1992 presidential election. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, who has vowed not to seek re-election, told the 5,093 delegates she hoped the new party was founded `` not only for the 1992 elections but to help our people face and overcome their problems.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> acknowledged the country must reinforce its newly won democracy by establishing disciplined national parties. Parties here have traditionally formed around personalities of their leaders rather than ideology. `` Without the organization of political beliefs and programs into disciplined parties, we would have only a riot of conflicting opinions but no effective action,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> said. She said political factionalism enabled her ousted predecessor, <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, to impose eight years of martial law in 1972. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> said the current political realignment was creating disenchantment among the Filipino public, who fear a return to the old-style politics of bickering and infighting that led to martial rule. Delegates to the inaugural convention included 108 of the 202 members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION>, six of the 23 senators, 42 provincial governors and more than 1,170 city and town mayors. Sen. <PERSON> Neptali </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, convention chairman, said he was not disappointed by Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s reluctance to give the party a ringing endorsement or to join its ranks. `` You do n't expect the president to say, ` this is my party,'' <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> said. `` I think her presence here is enough inspiration to add membership to the party.'' <PERSON> Mitra </PERSON> said Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> avoided a clearcut endorsement of the party as the principal administration party because `` she might be accused of playing politics.'' He told reporters the party was organized to consolidate political support for the government and establish a grass-roots, mass movement behind Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>. `` But there are others who do not believe in this thinking,'' <PERSON> Mitra </PERSON> said. He was referring to the refusal of 18 <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> members in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to join the new party. The Liberals, led by <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Jovito </PERSON> <PERSON> Salonga </PERSON>, are among six parties united in the government coalition. But the Liberals have disagreed with other pro-government parties and with some of the president's politically influential relatives. Last month, Vice President <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Laurel </LOCATION> and opposition Sen. <PERS