<HEAD>Judges Plan Videotape Experiment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Judicial Conference has announced an experiment that could eliminate court stenographers. The Judicial Conference, a 28-judge board which sets policy for the nation's federal courts, announced Thursday that it has approved a two-year experiment for some federal courts to videotape their proceedings. The experiment marks a radical departure for the federal judiciary because, unlike many of their state counterparts, the federal courts ban all electronic coverage of courtroom proceedings. The experiment, to be conducted in six trial courts and two appeals courts which have not been identified, is designed to find out whether videotapes should replace written documents as official records of trial and appellate court proceedings. Public access to the videotapes is `` something that has not been determined yet,'' said conference spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Sellers </PERSON>. The experiment, which will be supplemented by stenographic record, will be monitored by a committee led by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bilby </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz </LOCATION>.
