<HEAD>Many Doctors Misinform Patients In Nicotine Gum Use</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Doctors often incorrectly instruct patients on using nicotine gum or fail to prescribe it at all even though it can help heavy smokers quit, according to studies published today. `` Most internists prescribe nicotine gum to fewer than 25 percent of patients who try to quit smoking,'' said one of five smoking-related studies in today's Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` There is a widespread need for physician education about how to use nicotine gum more effectively.'' For instance, nearly 40 percent of 208 internists surveyed in the study said they would prescribe nicotine gum to help patients cut down on smoking, violating a key guideline for using it. The manufacturer's guidelines call for patients to stop smoking completely before using it. And one-fourth of the internists surveyed said they had recently prescribed sedatives to help patients stop smoking, although `` there is no evidence that sedatives are useful'' for that purpose, said the study by Dr. <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cummings </PERSON> and colleagues at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. `` I would guess that the confusion and difficulties with using the gum are very widespread,'' <PERSON> Cummings </PERSON> said. Nicotine gum, a prescription drug marketed under the trade name Nicorette by <ORGANIZATION> Lakeside </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceuticals </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>, can be an effective tool to help some people quit smoking, particularly heavy smokers, concluded three other studies in the journal. But one study found that 34 of 538 patients, or 6.8 percent, who were given nicotine gum to help them quit smoking were still chewing it after a year. Those long-term gum chewers also represented 25 percent of the patients who succeeded in staying off cigarettes for a year, said the report by researchers at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION>. `` I do n't think physicians ought to supply it just willy-nilly,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fortmann </PERSON>, an assistant professor at the <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>. `` Most people who've quit smoking did it before the gum was available ... So we're by no means advocating it. `` The gum should n't be seen as either a miracle or as a necessity, but as a useful adjunct.'' Another study in the journal found that heavy smokers _ those who consume more than 25 cigarettes daily _ are more physically addicted to nicotine and have a harder time quitting than people who smoke no more than 15 cigarettes a day. That study suggested nicotine gum might better help heavy smokers overcome withdrawal symptoms caused by their physical addiction when they stop. Lakeside spokesman <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Donaldson </PERSON> said the manufacturer estimates 2 million people have quit smoking by using nicotine gum as part of a stop-smoking program since Nicorette was introduced in 1985. He said the company had no reports of patients becoming addicted to nicotine from the gum itself. Any dependence on the gum `` is a transference'' of the patient's nicotine addiction from smoking and `` is part of the weaning process,'' <PERSON> Donaldson </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
