 A hotel bellhop honored for saving a handicapped man from his burning apartment after a fireman had given up says he does n't want to be recognized as a hero, `` Thank you was more than enough.'' Nonetheless, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cathcart </PERSON> was among 20 Americans and Canadians honored Thursday for their heroism by the <ORGANIZATION> Carnegie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hero </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Two of the heroes died in the performance of their deeds. <PERSON> Cathcart </PERSON>, who works at a <LOCATION> Catskill </LOCATION> mountains hotel, said he was walking home in <LOCATION> Ellenville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, on July 22, 1987, when he heard a woman screaming that her handicapped brother was trapped in a burning apartment. `` I thought to myself, ` Someone do something,''' <PERSON> Cathcart </PERSON> recalled in a telephone interview Thursday. `` A volunteer fireman said he could n't make it. Instead of getting all riled up, I tried to figure out what to do.'' <PERSON> Cathcart </PERSON> picked up a dirty towel from the ground, put it over his mouth, and went to the fiery second floor for <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> DeJesus </PERSON>, 33. `` He was trying to get himself up with his crutches. I put him up on my shoulders and ran down the steps. A lot of things were going to my mind, but I was n't thinking of my own health,'' <PERSON> Cathcart </PERSON> recalled. `` I did n't want to be recognized as a hero. Myself, I just felt good inside for helping another man. Thank you was more than enough. I know I'll always have a friend.'' Heroes receive $ 2,500 and a medal from the <ORGANIZATION> Carnegie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hero </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which was established by industrialist <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Carnegie </PERSON> in 1904 to recognize heroism by civilians in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. It has honored 77 people this year and 7,258 people since 1904. Others recognized Thursday were: _ <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chipley </PERSON>, 17, of <LOCATION> Estevan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saskatchewan </LOCATION>, who died helping in the rescue of a 16-year-old boy in an abandoned mine on Nov. 11, 1987 _ <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Paradis </PERSON>, 28, of <LOCATION> Chelsea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, who died of stab wounds after saving a woman from an assailant who had broken into her apartment in <LOCATION> Lynn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, on Oct. 26, 1987 _ <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 18, of <LOCATION> Wilkes-Barre </LOCATION>, who saved a 3-year-old boy from his burning apartment on Oct. 26, 1987 _ <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Dobbs </PERSON>, 46, of <LOCATION> Fairfax </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, who saved a man from drowning in the <LOCATION> Potomac </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> on Dec. 22, 1987 _ <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Brill </PERSON>, 24, of <LOCATION> Elkhart </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, who saved two women from drowning in their car, which had plunged into the <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Joseph </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> on Oct. 21, 1987 _ <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Conner </PERSON>, 45, of <LOCATION> Trenton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, who saved a girl from a burning car in <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, on Sept. 26, 1987 _ <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Luzak </PERSON>, 42, of <LOCATION> Walton </LOCATION>, <LOCAT