<SECOND>PM-Olympic Protests,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radicals Mount Anti-Olympic Protests On Eve Of Games</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of radical students shouting `` Yankee go home!'' mounted protests against the Olympics today on the eve of Games and burned an effigy of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. Students staged protests at three schools in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> to demand the Olympics be shared with communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and to denounce the government of President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo. The Olympics start Saturday. `` Oppose dictator's Olympics!'' and `` Crush military aggression!'' students yelled. About 300 protesters armed with firebombs and clubs marched out of <ORGANIZATION> Kookmin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> to fight riot police after burning effigies of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>, as well as a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flag. But riot police watched from a distance and did not intervene as the protesters repeatedly blocked traffic. Students, one of whom hurled a single firebomb at a passing police truck and missed, tired of taunting police and dispersed. About 500 students took part in a similar protest at <ORGANIZATION> Seoul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in the south of the capital. They marched to the gate and burned an effigy of <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>. Riot police in green combat fatigues and black, visored helmets watched but did not intervene. The students made no move to attack the police. The protesters then marched to a gym on the campus where Olympic table tennis events are to be held and yelled anti-Olympic slogans outside the building before dispersing. A small anti-Olympic protest was also held at <ORGANIZATION> Yonsei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> with less than 100 students taking part. Anti-Olympic protests have been small by Korean standards, and the radicals have failed to attract support. Violent clashes with riot police have dropped sharply in recent days as the number of students taking part has dwindled. A few onlookers even shouted abuse at protesters at <LOCATION> Kookmin </LOCATION>, accusing them of trying to wreck the Olympics. `` Go home. You are shaming our nation,'' screamed an angry old man. The radicals are demanding the Olympics be shared with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to promote reunification of the <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>, divided since 1945. Radicals also contend the <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> government is a front for military rule and is using the Olympics to cement its rule with aid from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The great majority of <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION>, including most students, want the Olympics to be a major success. `` Students know the people are against these demonstrations,'' a student leader said today. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> is boycotting the Olympics because its demand to be a co-host of the Games was rejected. The International Olympic Committee said the Games are awarded to a single city and can not be shared.
