<FIRST>r a PM-WPPSSTrial     09-16 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-WPPSS Trial,0596</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Debacle Encompassed All, Says Attorney For Engineers
^By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Accusations against 19 defendants in the fraud trial over the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supply </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION>'s default on $ 2.25 billion in bonds amounts to `` fraud by hindsight,'' a defense lawyer says `` There is no evidence to support charges of conspiracy,'' <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Nickles </PERSON>, representing the engineering firm of <ORGANIZATION> Ebasco </ORGANIZATION>, said in opening statements Thursday. Jurors were told by other defense attorneys that utility officials who sat on the system's board of directors were part-time public servants who relied on experts and had nothing to gain by misleading investors who bought bonds in the two nuclear plants. `` These people always acted in good faith,'' said <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Malanca </PERSON>, who represents 12 of the 16 public utilities that are among defendants. `` They had no motive to do wrong.'' <PERSON> Malanca </PERSON> opened the defendants' case by disputing plaintiff attorneys' arguments that utility members of the <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> board controlled the supply system and plotted to defraud bond buyers. Defendants, including another engineering firm and a financial adviser to <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION>, are accused of making misrepresentations and withholding crucial information from investors who bought bonds to finance construction of two nuclear power plants. Plaintiffs include more than 24,000 bond buyers in the case, which resulted from the 1983 default by <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> on the $ 2.25 billion in bonds. It was the biggest default in the history of the municipal bond market. The trial began last week. The judge excused jurors until Monday, when opening arguments by defense attorneys were to resume. <PERSON> Nickles </PERSON> said what happened to the WPPSS projects was happening to the entire nuclear industry by the late 1970s. He said plant-construction prices dramatically escalated because of inflation and required changes to make nuclear plants safer. And the 1979 Three Mile Island accident, he said, `` wrecked the nuclear industry.'' <PERSON> Malanca </PERSON> told jurors that the plaintiffs would have them believe the 16 utility defendants had the power to control federal and state agencies, and were able to induce major engineering and financial firms to knowingly make false claims on official bond statements. But the utilities were relatively small, and were far down on the pecking order among the energy powers in the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>, he said. The federal <ORGANIZATION> Bonneville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, he said, dominated the region. While <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> in the 1970s, with five nuclear plants under construction, was also a major player in the energy scene, said <PERSON> Malanca </PERSON>, the utility officials that directed it were part-time participants. He said they considered their appointments to the board a matter of civic duty, went to meetings only periodically, hired the best experts they could find, and generally followed directions of those experts and <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION>. The supply system staff had more power in directing <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> and board members were not even to speak to the media as representatives of <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION>, he said. `` If they did anything wrong, they were acting as board members of the supply system, not of the utilities,'' he said. He stressed that public utility officials are not paid, receiving only per diem allowances for their work. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Bromley </PERSON>, another defense lawyer, said utilities from the 23-member <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> board sent one representative each to the supply system. But, he said, the utilities had no control at all over how that representative voted and did n't stand a chance of controlling the supply system. The supply system was created in 1957 to build and operate major power-generating facilities in the Northwest.
