<HEAD>Dollar Steady in Thin Trading, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar was trading steadily in thin late-morning trading in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> today, with players saying they expected the dollar to stay in a narrow range throughout the session. Gold prices moved lower. Foreign exchange dealers in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> said that volume was limited and that there were few commercial orders as activity wound down for the weekend. They said that the market remained bullish about the dollar due to the narrower-than-expected <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> July trade deficit reported Wednesday. But they cautioned that the general opinion was that the world's major central banks appeared content with the dollar's present levels, and that any attempt to push it much higher would invite intervention `` I see the dollar gaining ground, but nobody wants to be the first the try stepping over 1.88 -LRB- West German -RRB- marks,'' said a trader in <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> with a major Italian commercial bank. He predicted that the dollar would trade within a range of between 1.87 marks and 1.88 marks today. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where the business day ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s begins, the dollar rose 0.31 yen to a closing 133.76 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 134.10 yen. Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Thursday: _ 1.8741 West German marks, down from 1.8775 _ 1.5810 Swiss francs, down from 1.5820 _ 6.3735 French francs, down from 6.3790 _ 2.1133 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1160 _ 1,397.25 Italian lire, down from 1,398.87 _ 1.2235 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2225 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound rose to $ 1.6755, Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 417 a troy ounce, down from $ 417.75 bid late Thursday. At mid-morning Friday, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 417.30 In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 417.20, down from $ 417.50 bid late Thur