<HEAD>U.S. Officials Site Possible Removal Of Bases From Philippines</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th graf, Other officials, to UPDATE
with Gorbachev statement.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Top <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials are for the first time talking seriously about removing military bases from the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, and the chief <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> negotiator says the country is preparing for such a possibility but still negotiating. Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said Thursday the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> wants to keep giant <ORGANIZATION> Clark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Subic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> and other installations in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> but `` there are alternatives which we are having now to examine.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said talks in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> on bases compensation and other issues `` basically are n't going well.'' On Wednesday, <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> told visiting Philippine Foreign Minister <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON>, in what one official described as blunt terms, that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is prepared to pull out of the bases if the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> insists on too much compensation. Other officials have suggested they might be relocated to <LOCATION> Guam </LOCATION> or elsewhere in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>, with estimates of the cost of such a move ranging over $ 10 billion. Defense officials have said in the past that the bases are vital to security of a vast area stretching from <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> into the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said in a speech today that the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> is ready to give up its base at <LOCATION> Cam </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ranh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, if <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces leave the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have said this would not be a balanced exchange. <PERSON> Cam </PERSON> <PERSON> Ranh </PERSON> <PERSON> Bay </PERSON> is the Soviets' major naval deployment base abroad, while <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> and <PERSON> Subic </PERSON> are the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>'s largest foreign bases. <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON>, in an interview Thursday, said the two sides in the negotiations now in recess are not far apart on how much the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration should seek from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in direct payment for use of the bases, but several other issues in the talks remain unresolved. `` Both sides agree that the hard component -LRB- cash -RRB- of our mutual proposals were not too far apart and that in addition we would be looking for creative ways of raising the level of the compensation to that which was proposed by the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON> said. He said additional help might come in the form of procurement of Philippine products and the writing off of some of the nation's $ 26 billion foreign debt. <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON> did not say how much aid has been offered by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> panel, but congressional sources have said it is close to $ 500 million, including a doubling of direct bases-related aid to $ 360 million for fiscal 1989. <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON> declined to say how much the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> originally wanted, but <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> news reports have put the demand as high as $ 1.2 billion a year. <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON> said he was not surprised by <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>'s remarks about pulling out and asserted that the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> is preparing for a loss of the bases. He said studies show that conversion of the bases to civilian use could provide even more benefits, including replacement of the thousands of jobs that would be lost if the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> pulls out. He said that while the bases provide significant economic benefit, even American analysts agree that their security value to the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> is minimal. `` Your own analysts and your own leaders stress the priority importance of the global strategy that is fulfilled by these bases,'' he said. <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON> said unresolved issues in the bases talks include the storage of nuclear weapons on the bases, ownership of improvements to the bases, procurement policies and the write-off of debts for military equipment. `` We have not gotten anything out of the American panel,'' he said. <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON> said he is discussing the bases issue with a variety of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials but has not moved the negotiations from <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Surveys of Filipinos show only a small percentage of outright opposition to the bases, he said, but a large number of people say they would want the bases out if the Americans do not improve the bases agreement, including additional compensation. <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON>, who lived in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> self-exile during the last decade of ex-President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' rule, said he has found Democrats more responsive on Philippine issues than Republicans, but he said the views of the two parties on the bases appear to be the same. <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON> plans to meet <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> again at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> at the end of the mon