<HEAD>Case Count To Reach 365,000 By '92, CDC Predicts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The number of AIDS cases in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will jump nearly five-fold by 1992, and about 263,000 people will have died from the disease by then, the national <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> predicts. As of this week, 72,766 AIDS cases have been reported to the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>; 41,064 people, or 56 percent, are dead. By the end of 1992, the number of cases will hit 365,000, and 72 percent of those patients will be dead, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> says. The predictions came Thursday in a report summarizing the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s latest quarterly report on AIDS to the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'s Domestic Policy Council Actual AIDS reporting has run slightly higher than predicted; the agency in 1986 predicted 15,800 cases in 1986 and 23,000 in 1987, and the actual totals were 17,100 and 25,200, respectively. `` We think they're very close,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Dondero </PERSON>, an AIDS specialist at the Atlanta-based health agency. `` I think the message is that, at least for the first couple of years, this ... method gives some pretty reliable estimates.'' The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 issued its AIDS predictions for 1991, which forecast 270,000 cases by the end of that year. In the report released Thursday, the agency predicts 80,000 cases of AIDS in 1992 alone, with 66,000 deaths that year. A total of 172,000 living AIDS patients will require medical care in 1992, at a cost of $ 5 billion to $ 13 billion, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> predicts. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> also said its current estimate of 1 million to 1.5 million Americans currently infected with the virus which causes AIDS is `` a reasonable working estimate,'' based on mathematical analysis by experts convened by the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> in April. Thursday's report noted that the national infection estimate has remained the same since it was devised in 1986. The rate is about 0.4 percent to 0.6 percent. `` This does not mean that no new infections have occurred,'' the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The 1986 estimate was based on preliminary data, and was probably too high -LRB- at the time -RRB-.''
