<HEAD>Los Angeles to Pay Homeless for Possessions Destroyed in Sweep</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Forty-one homeless people whose possessions were destroyed in a police sweep will receive $ 500 each, according to terms of a settlement that some recipients said could free them from life on the street. The city admitted no wrongdoing in the agreement, which provides $ 20,500 to be divided among those affected in the incident. City officials confirmed the settlement Thursday but declined to comment. The claims resulted from a June police sweep of two homeless camps in the shadow of City Hall. Authorities said they gave an estimated 50 people 30 minutes to clear out, but many were away looking for food or work. They returned to find their possessions _ including medicine, identification papers and clothing _ were gone. Although the agreement does n't guarantee that such sweeps wo n't be conducted again, lawyers representing the homeless said it is an important victory that should discourage officials from similar seizures `` I believe this has already affected the attitude and practice of police everywhere in this city,'' said attorney <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, who filed the claims on behalf of the homeless men and women. Many of the recipients said they would use the $ 500 to find permanent shelter. `` We're going to get a place and get married,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, 27, of his plans for the money. `` I'm trying to get ahead, I'm trying to have a future,'' said <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, who added he has been sleeping on the street while studying word processing at a technical school. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON>, 48, said he hopes to `` get a place and get off the street. The streets are making me old.'' However, <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON>, an activist for the homeless and one of the 41 to file a claim against the city, warned: `` Five hundred dollars is not going to get anybody off the street.''
