<HEAD>Gorbachev Calls for Improved Ties With China, Renews Summit Call</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gorbachev</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> made another pitch today for improving Soviet relations with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and renewed a call for a Sino-Soviet summit. `` We stand for the full normalization of relations with the People's Republic of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, for their development up to the level adequate to our two countries' responsiblity for peaceful world policy,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said in a major speech in the Siberian city of <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> first proposed a summit with <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> in a speech in the eastern Soviet city of <LOCATION> Vladivostok </LOCATION>, near the Chinese border, on July 28, 1986. Chinese Communist Party General Secretary <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON> said last month the first Sino-Soviet summit since 1960 was possible if <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> first urged <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> to leave <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. Since the <LOCATION> Vladivostok </LOCATION> speech, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has taken several steps to remove obstacles to improving ties with the Chinese. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has listed the impediments as the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> intervention in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s support of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s occupation of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and Soviet troops stationed along the Soviet border with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> has moved to clear some of the obstacles. In May, it began withdrawing its troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and has pulled some of its forces out of <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION>, which borders <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> also has offered to accept <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s request that the two cou