<HEAD>Walesa Meets with Authorities on Future of Solidarity</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland-Dialogue, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with talks beginning, quotes. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and a team of union activists met with Interior Minister <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszcak </PERSON> today to set an agenda for talks on the future of the banned trade union. The meeting, which included at least 10 Solidarity members or advisers, marked the first time since the union was banned in 1982 that so many union activists sat down with government officials. The third encounter between <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and the government began this afternoon at an undisclosed location outside <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Jacek </PERSON> <PERSON> Ambroziak </PERSON>. `` After two meetings of our chairman alone, there is now a serious delegation,'' said senior Solidarity adviser <PERSON> Bronislaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON>. The expansion of the number of participants in the talks `` is a serious step in the right direction,'' <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON> said. `` A Solidarity delegation is talking to the authorities at last.'' At least 23 people, including 11 officials led by <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> and two priests, were participating in the talks. Earlier <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said he was optimistic that broader talks with the government on Solidarity would begin soon. The comment came after <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> met for more than four hours Thursday with <PERSON> Kiszcak </PERSON>, his second meeting with Polish authorities in six years. The two agreed Thursday to continue working toward an early start of talks on <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s future with broader participation. They also agreed to expand the group of participants at today's working meeting and to agree on the topics, composition, as well as the procedure and work schedule of the later talks, the state-run news service <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> told reporters after the meeting that `` the atmosphere is encouraging'' but difficule problems remain. The government agreed to the talks and <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> moved to halt a wave of strikes last month that posed the most serious threat to the government since Solidarity was crushed in 1981. It was declared illegal a year later. Today's meeting was to include some leaders of Solidarity strikes last month as well as at least five members of the official trade union alliance OPZZ, said <PERSON> Franciszek </PERSON> <PERSON> Ciemny </PERSON>, an OPZZ spokesman. In another development, an official newspaper published an interview with <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> for the first time since the imposition of martial law in December 1981. The interview in the September issue of the monthly publication <PERSON> Konfrontacje </PERSON>, which came out Thursday, seemed to underline <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>'s return to official respectability and the new emphasis on considering divergent views The monthly, sponsored by the official national unity organization <ORGANIZATION> PRON </ORGANIZATION>, interviewed the Solidarity leader at his home on Sept. 1, the day a strike at the <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> shipyard led by <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> ended. `` You are the first Polish journalists from the officially published press to come to me asking for an interview since Dec. 13, 1981,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said, referring to the exact date of the martial law crackdown that suppressed Solidarity, the first independent trade union movement allowed in the Soviet bloc. `` There must be Solidarity,'' the interview quoted <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> as saying. But in it he added, `` It certainly does not have to be a carbon copy of that of 1981.''
