<HEAD>Court Says EPA Need Not Recalculate Mileage Data</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court today struck down two previous orders that had directed the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> to recalculate automobile fuel economy ratings. The order by the full <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> here relieves the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> of any obligation to comply with the court's previous orders to recalculate the fuel economy ratings according to a method that could cost <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> millions of dollars in fines The decision today, made in a brief order by the court's 11 members, reversed a 5-5 vote taken May 17 that had upheld a 1986 ruling by a three-judge panel that the fuel standards be recalculated. In the previous vote, the court divided along bitter ideological lines over whether the Center for Auto Safety and other petitioners had standing to challenge the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s 1985 decision to relax the fuel-economy standards. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> action had lowered penalties that <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> would be assessed for failing to meet fleet-wide fuel economy standards set under the Environmental Policy and Conservation Act of 1975. The law requires manufacturers to be fined $ 5 for each tenth of a mile a car model falls short of the miles-per-gallon standard set by the EPA regulations. Manufacturers are given credits for models that surpass the standards that can be carried over to subsequent model years. The court said today that after considering the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s motion to reconsider that decision, `` we have decided that our original disposition was not an appropriate one.'' `` We now hold that as a majority of the ... court was unable to satisfy itself that the court had jurisdiction, the court should not have taken any affirmative action on the merits, including reinstatement of the panel opinion,'' the court said in an unsigned order. In May, the court had said that it would uphold the 1986 ruling but that that holding would not become a legal precedent because the circuit judges could not agree on the issue of legal standing.
