enforcement, picks up 4th graf pvs, Standing across ...; deletes
grafs 14-15, 17-19 pvs for length</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, saying the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administation has short-changed the war on drugs, promised today he would double the number of federal drug agents and hire more federal prosecutors. `` We are going to give state and local law enforcement officers the money to fight the war,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said in remarks prepared for delivery at the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION>. `` We're not going to try to nickel and dime you to death, as this administation has done,'' he said. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said that as president he would double the number of federal Drug Enforcement Administation officials over five years. Aides to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said he was prepared to spend $ 50 million to hire 600 new agents next year toward the goal of 2,800 new agents. He said he would put 100 of those new agents in southern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, where he was campaigning today. The <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign said the candidate was committed to hiring 800 more federal prosecutors to help handle drug cases and other crimes. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> ridiculed remarks by Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> two days ago in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, quoting <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as saying he is `` almost haunted'' by severe drug problems in inner cities. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said, `` American children do not need our pity. They need strong leaders and first rate law enforcement officers ... They do n't need a change of heart in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. They need a change of leadership.'' On Thursday, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> traveled to the charred forests of Yellowstone National Park to show support for firefighters. Standing across a river gorge from a blackened hillside, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> refused to be drawn into the debate in the West over whether the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration should have acted sooner. Following National Park Service policy, the government allowed those fires that were ignited naturally to burn themselves out until late July. `` This is n't the time to discuss what might have been or should be,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` Everybody agrees that once the fires are out, it'll be a good time to sit down and think through exactly how we deal with this problem in the future.'' The Democratic nominee, putting aside his newly aggressive demeanor for a moment, sounded nearly as cautious when asked about <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s assault on his economic record as governor of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> _ an area <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> made the centerpiece of his candidacy. `` I'll be responding to that sometime next week,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said at first. `` ... Good luck to Mr. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the Republican nominee, said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' state led in spending increases and was second in tax increases under his administrations and called him `` the gold medal winner in he tax-and-spend competition.'' Several minutes later, appearing to reconsider the notion of allowing <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s charges to go unanswered, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> delivered a response without prompting. Arriving in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> later, he again volunteered a reaction. `` We've balanced 10 budgets in a row, we have a 3 percent unemployment rate, we have more jobs than people to fill them, personal income is rising at the second fastest rate in the nation, and we've cut taxes five times in the last five yearrs,'' he said. `` What Mr. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has given us is a mountain of debt, record deficits, and record trade deficts, and an economic future which does not bode well for the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people.'' The issue of when to battle forest fires has produced divisions in the <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> states and poses political pitfalls. Interior Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> has suggested the policy may be changed. But the policy of letting fires burn themselves out unless they threaten lives or structures has won support from some environmentalists, who argue that fire is a natural process that makes way for new growth. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said he wanted to hear more about the issue, but he recognized that argument. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has campaigned in the <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> states and, at the height of his midsummer popularity, aides were speaking hopefully of the nominee's chances in those states _ especially <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>. But as the race has tightened everywhere, the <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> states _ which have been reliably Republican in presidential races even though they elect Democratic state officials _ are looking increasingly difficult for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>.
