<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 1254EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Greenhouse-Hurricanes     09-16 0770</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greenhouse-Hurricanes,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greenhouse Effect May Worsen Hurricanes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hurricanes of the future may be even more powerful than any that have come before, as a result of the so-called greenhouse effect warming of the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, a scientist is warning. <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Emanuel </PERSON>, of the meteorology department at <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>, expressed his concern even as Hurricane <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>, perhaps the most powerful tropical storm of the century, was churning a path of destruction through the Gulf of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Because hurricanes gain their energy from the warm ocean waters in tropical areas, rising temperatures could increase the strength of these storms in the future, he explained in a telephone interview. `` Over the warmest parts of the oceans, a change in sea-surface temperature of 1 degree Celsius -LRB- 1.6 degrees Fahrenheit -RRB- will change the minimum sustainable pressure in a hurricane by 15 to 20'' millibars, <PERSON> Emanuel </PERSON> reported. The pressure in the center of a hurricane is generally considered a good indication of its strength, with lower pressures indicating a more powerful storm. Normal sea level pressure is 1,013 millibars, while in a powerful storms like <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> readings can drop into the high 800s. <PERSON> Emanuel </PERSON> commented, however, that it's too soon to tell whether <PERSON> Hurricane </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> is a product of the greenhouse warming. `` This is kind of an extraordinary hurricane, but I do n't think we can take it as an indication we are seeing any kind of trend,'' he said. `` If the predictions of some climate models come true, and that's a pretty big if, we can expect to see some more intense hurricanes in 50 years or so.'' That means the strong storms of the future would be more powerful than the strong ones of today, he explained, although there would n't necessarily be more storms. There generally seems to be a limit to how low the pressure can fall in even the strongest storms, explained <PERSON> Emanuel </PERSON>, but warmer ocean waters could lower that limit. And that, he said, is what could result in the stronger storms. The greenhouse effect has been widely reported in recent years. Climate experts explain it as the result of increasing carbon dioxide and other polluting gases in the atmosphere. Those gases allow the incoming sunlight to continue to warm the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, but block some outgoing radiation, leading to a gradual increase in the planet's temperature. It is a situation similar to that of a greenhouse where heat from the sun is captured to warm plants. Studies by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> concluded that carbon dioxide in the atmosphere has increased by 25 percent since the mid-1800s and continues to grow. Scientists have estimated that the overall temperature of the Earth has risen by more than 1 degree Fahrenheit over the same time, and could rise by another 2 degrees over the next few decades. Computerized models, using complex mathematical formulas to predict the result of such a warming, have warned of a variety of dire consequences ranging from drought over croplands to melting of the polar ice caps, raising sea levels and inundating coastal communities. <PERSON> Emanuel </PERSON> is the author of a study, `` Toward a General Theory of Hurricanes,'' which appears in the July-August edition of American Scientist. In it he noted that while many things about the giant tropical storms remain a mystery, in recent years scientists have come to a better understanding of the storms. The power for hurricanes, he explained, comes from the transfer of moisture and energy from the oceans into the overlying air. This air rises, forming a low pressure area, and wind from surrounding area begins blowing in a spiral toward that center, bringing in more moisture from the warm ocean. Since the rate of evaporation increases with wind speed, the faster the wind the more water and energy it can pick up in the storm. The inward-flowing air can not get to the actual center of the storm because the laws of physics would cause it to increase its spin to an infinite velocity, <PERSON> Emanuel </PERSON> explains. Thus, at some point, the wind stops moving inward and begins to ascend, forming the well-known cloudy eye-wall of a hurricane. Because ocean heat drives these big storms, scientists have found that among the conditions necessary before a hurricane can form is an ocean temperature of 26 degrees Celsius _ about 82 degrees Fahrenheit _ and that warm water needs to extend down about 60 meters, or 165 feet. In addition, the storms will not form if there are strong cross winds, which disrupt the rising motion that helps form the center of the storms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
