<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said today that Democratic rival <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is a campaign convert on defense issues who is trying to fool <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> voters _ and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> leaders _ by `` riding around in a tank for 10 minutes.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said photographs of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> wearing a military helmet and riding in an M-1 tank at a defense contractor's plant in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> earlier this week were at odds with his record on national defense. `` All I can do is cite his position,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, declaring that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has opposed the railroad-based MX missile, the Midgetman missile and the B-1 bomber. `` Now suddenly he rides around in a tank, jumps out of the tank, takes off the helmet and comes on with different positions,'' the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> nominee said as he toured the <ORGANIZATION> Buckeye </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> plant in <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> under the silent gaze of steelworkers, some wearing <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> T-shirts. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> opposes the MX and Midgetman missile programs and initially expressed opposition to the B-1 bomber, although he said later that production of the aircraft should be allowed to proceed. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he was encouraged by the reception he received from the steelworkers at the plant where his grandfather, <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Prescott </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, was once president. About 150 employees stood quietly throughout the speech, neither jeering nor applauding. `` Admittedly, the applause meter did n't go off the chart,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` nor did the boo meter go off the chart. These days we measure things by both meters.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was `` way over in left field'' on some issues of concern to blue-collar workers. `` These people do n't want gun control. They do favor the death penalty,'' the vice president said. In Findlay, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, a city that calls itself `` <LOCATION> Flag </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> U.S.A. </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> declared that `` the flag is back'' and then seemed to stumble into the Pledge of Allegiance. At a flag-draped rally, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` What is it all about? It's the symbol of these <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, and to the liberty for which it stands, one nation under God with freedom and justice for all And let's never forget it.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told reporters in <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is tailoring his message in an effort gain the support of Democrats voters who previously had voted for President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. `` He's gone to states like this, found that his message of ... cutting unilaterally on these weapons systems is not popular, and so now he's been made over,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` He's coming out with policies quite different, but which ones do you believe? You believe this 30-day conversion as you climb out of a tank?'' The vice president added: `` The tanks did not fit. It's time to take another message to <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>. It's very straightforward. You can not fool the Soviet leadership by knocking <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s defense for 10 years and riding around in a tank for 10 minutes. ... You ca n't fool the American people.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also made an apparent misstatement, saying he stands for anti-Semitism, when asked about the resignation of six pro-Bush campaign aides on ethnic groups who allegedly had pro-Nazi or anti-Semitic ties. He said the aides left voluntarily to avoid diverting attention from campaign issues. `` I hope I stand for anti-bigotry, anti-Semitism, anti-racism,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` That is what drives me. It's one of the things that I feel very strongly about.'' The <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> nominee said in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> on Thursday that he hoped former White House aide <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> would be exonerated of all charges stemming from his role in the Iran-Contra affair. But <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> refused to rule out a presidential pardon if North is found guilty. And today, he ducked a question whether he would offer North a job in any <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> stopped in <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> on his return to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> after a two-day campaign swing through <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> highlighted by a statistical assault on <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as an Olympic-class `` tax-and-spend'' governor of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. Trying to project a disastrous <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy under a <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> administration, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor had presided over a state that lost 26,000 jobs since 1983. The text of the speech said `` manufacturing jobs,'' but <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> skipped over the word. Press Secretary <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> said the omission was inadvertent. Official figures also show that under <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the state's job market as a whole has seen a five-year increase of 230,000 jobs to more than offset the loss of manufacturing jobs. On another point, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> in the last two years `` has turned a surplus into a growing budget deficit that according to Massachussetts legislators appears to be approaching $ 500 to $ 700 million for fiscal 1989.'' In fact, the state has no deficit now, and <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> said the vice president was only referring to the future projected deficit. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> in fiscal 1988 had a $ 67 million surplus after cutting $ 450 million in spending and dipping into some reserve accounts. Critics questioned the surplus and said it could only be the result of tax and fee increases, government borrowing and a `` raid'' on the state pension fund. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also noted that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has borrowed about $ 200 million a month since June for operations, and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called it `` last-ditch borrowing.'' But <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> says the short-term loans are needed to cover municipal aid that is now dispensed in a lump sum annually instead of in periodic installments as was the case before 1986, and that helps the local municipalities avoid heavy borrowing while waiting for state aid. On taxes, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> listed <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> as second in the nation in growth in per capita taxes since 1963. That means taxes are higher per person than in any state but <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>. But it is not due to a tax hike by <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> economics adviser <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Boskin </PERSON> acknowledged. In fact there have been no broad-based tax increases in <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' two terms that began in 1983 Tax revenues went way up due to growth in income and other economic factors, <PERSON> Boskin </PERSON> said, adding that the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> criticism is that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> let the taxes rise without instituting any relief for taxpayers. `` He's allowed them to rise without returning them,'' to taxpayers or seeking tax limitation measures as other states have done, said <PERSON> Boskin </PERSON>. There have been numerous tax cuts during <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' last two terms.
