<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A tax-reform group said it will appeal a court ruling that overturned Proposition 62, the 1986 initiative that requires local governments to seek voter approval for local taxes. Proposition 62, a fine-tuning of the landmark tax-capping Proposition 13 that was championed by the late tax reformer <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Jarvis </PERSON>, was overturned Thursday by the state's <ORGANIZATION> 4th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeal </ORGANIZATION>. The unanimous decision said requiring voter approval constitutes a `` gross interference with the fiscal responsiblity of local governments.'' `` It's a sad day for the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> taxpayer,'' said <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reduction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. The anti-tax group campaigned for Proposition 62 after <PERSON> Jarvis </PERSON> died in 1986. <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> said his organization would appeal the ruling to the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. If the high court refuses to hear the case, <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> said his group would consider another initiative campaign. The appellate court reversed a decision in January by a <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judge, who upheld Proposition 62 against a challenge brought by the city of <LOCATION> Westminster </LOCATION>. The appellate court ruling said <PERSON> Westminster </PERSON> has authority to impose a tax on utility users without a citywide vote. A similar case is before the state's 1st <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGAN