<HEAD>Survivors Recall Worse Giants Than Gilbert</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hurricane Gilbert Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN PLATERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 While <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> followed the destructive path of Hurricane <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> this week, he recalled the 1935 hurricane that claimed 50 relatives when it blasted the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Keys </LOCATION> with 200 mph wind and a 15-foot wall of water. `` I've been following this thing and I know the 1935 hurricane was tougher _ no maybe about that,'' said <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>, who lost his mother, three sisters, grandparents, aunts, uncles, nephews and cousins in the Labor Day hurricane, one of only two Category 5 hurricanes to make <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> landfall since record-keeping began. `` When I see the pictures from <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, you can see tall coconut palm trees still standing. There was n't one left on my island _ only stumps,'' <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>, 69, said by telephone Thursday from his daughter's home in <LOCATION> Frostproof </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> was a Category 4 storm when it devastated <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> this week, then strengthened to Category 5, which signifies sustained wind speed greater than 155 mph and interior barometric pressure less than 27.17 inches and other factors After crossing <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Yucatan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> had declined to Category 3 on its way to landfall near the Texas-Mexican border Friday. It had killed more than 50 people. <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>, then 17, was in the center of the 1935 hurricane's 14-mile-wide swath that destroyed a railroad, peeled the <ORGANIZATION> Matecumbe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Keys </ORGANIZATION> down to bare rock and killed 600, 408 in the Keys The retired carpenter still lives at <LOCATION> Islamorada </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Matecumbe </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheets </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hurricane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> at its peak was bigger in size and stronger in barometric pressure than the one that struck Sept. 2, 1935, although the earlier one was more powerful when it struck land. The other Category 5 hurricane to make <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> landfall was <PERSON> Camille </PERSON>, which killed 256 in the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> coastal area in 1969. In an interview at the time of the 50-year anniversary of the Keys hurricane, <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> relived the giant storm that was forecast to move into the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Straits </LOCATION> between <LOCATION> Key </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. But after a morning of sunshine, winds became ferocious and heavy rain fell. What was known then as the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Weather Bureau was unaware the hurricane had changed course. `` At 8 p.m., it got so black you could n't see your hand in front of your face,'' <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> said. He and his family sought refuge in a nearby building. `` The building began to shake and muddy water came in under the door. My father said we'd have to leave the building. He told us to grab hold of each other and try to hang together. `` We opened the back door and became separated. I was holding onto my sisters and nephews, but we were pulled apart,'' he said. <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> grabbed the door frame as the building toppled. `` There was debris everywhere. It was a boiling pot. The water rose quickly and my leg got caught. I stretched my neck and cupped my hands over my mouth as the water got higher. `` I heard a voice in the distance and I kept yelling at the person to keep yelling. Later, I worked down the pile of trash and my face pushed into something. It was my father; the voice I heard in the distance, he had been only an arm's length away.'' `` One of my cousins was found 40 miles from here,'' recalled <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>. `` She was still holding her baby in her arms.''
