<SECOND>AM-Minimum Wage, Bjt,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Democrats Proposing to Expand Subminimum Wage for Students</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> offered Friday to expand slightly an existing subminimum wage for full-time students to head off what they called a `` hire'em and fire'em'' 90-day training wage backed by Republicans. Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., offered an amendment to his bill raising the minimum wage from its current $ 3.35 an hour to $ 4.55 an hour by 1991 that would allow employers to hire up to 12 students instead of the six now allowed for up to 20 hours a week at 85 percent of the minimum wage Only about 100,000 students are now earning the $ 2.85 subminimum wage, according to <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials, compared with 515,000 students in 1978. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said his proposal would allow employers to double the number of students at the subminimum wage on their payrolls. The tactic was aimed at heading off a Republican amendment by Sen. <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> to establish an 80 percent training wage for newly hired workers for up to 90 days. <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> indicated that Republicans were unwilling to vote Friday on <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s student wage, putting off the key <ORGANIZATION> Republican-Democratic </ORGANIZATION> showdown on the politically volatile minimum wage issue until next week, eight weeks before the November election. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, R-Ind., <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s running mate, in the past have all conditioned any increase in the minimum wage to a massive expansion of the subminimum wage <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, campaigning in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, refused again Friday to specify how big of an increase in the minimum wage he favored. `` I do n't know how much of an increase,'' he said, but repeated that any upward adjustment should be coupled with a differential for a lower training wage. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, silent on the subject in recent days, offered an amendment while the bill was still in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> in June to couple a minimum wage increase to $ 4 an hour over two years with a subminimum training wage. The amendment was never voted on. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> complained none of the Republican training wage proposals require employers to provide any training. He said the real purpose was to give employers a `` windfall'' lower wage in jobs that have turnover rates of up to 400 percent a year. `` Who honestly believes that it takes three months for someone to learn to mop a floor or change the sheets on a bed?'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. `` This is a pure and simple wage cut.'' He said the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> proposal would provide employers with a powerful incentive to `` throw working families out on the street once every 90 days'' and replace them with a new force of trainees. `` This is the hire'em and fire'em wage, maybe we can call it the churn'em and burn'em wage,'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. `` The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> push will turn <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s working people into vagabonds and gypsies, thrown from job to job every three months. Can this be what <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> means when he talks about a kinder, gentler <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>?'' <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> called <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s counterproposal for an expansion of the currently allowed student waivers a `` not really very effective bureaucratic way of doing things.'' `` The purpose of the training wage is not to help full-time students,'' <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said. `` The purpose is to open the door of opportunity for those who have nothing, who are under-educated, unskilled.'' <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> cited various studies estimating that increasing the minimum wage would cause the loss of between 200,000 and 800,000 new jobs over the next three years. `` The reason 16 million new jobs _ 12 million of them at $ 10 an hour or more _ have been created -LRB- since 1981 -RRB- is because we have n't had an increase in the minimum wage,'' he said The federally mandated wage floor has been frozen at $ 3.35 since January 1981, the longest time in its 50-year history without an increase. Meanwhile, its purchasing power has dropped 30 percent to $ 2.60 measured in today's dollars. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s bill would raise by 40-cent increments each year to $ 3.75 in 1989, $ 4.15 in 1989 and $ 4.55 in 1990 _ a total of 35.8 percent over the three years. It also would increase the exemption for small businesses from the current threshold of $ 362,000 in gross sales to $ 500,000. According to <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> figures, about 6.7 million workers were paid the minimum wage or less in 1986. But the bill also would directly benefit 11.5 million other workers earning between $ 3.35 and $ 4.50. House Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, D-Tex., said Friday that the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> is awaiting <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> action before considering the issue `` The likelihood is we'll take it up, vote, pass it,'' he said.
