<HEAD>Building Collapse That Killed 28 Sparks New Safety Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal officials are proposing new rules aimed at preventing disasters like last year's collapse of an apartment building that killed 28 construction workers. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Occupational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s proposed rules may not be implemented until next summer, after the administration evaluates comment on the plan The proposal applies only to lift-slab techniques, which were being used when the partially completed L'Ambiance Plaza collapsed. The technique is a seldom-used method in which concrete floor slabs are poured on the ground, one on top of the other. After the slabs are cured, they are jacked upwards along vertical steel columns, then fastened at their proper levels. An <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> official, <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Gurnham </PERSON>, said the rules clarify the requirement that all non-essential workers be cleared from a lift-slab building while the floors are being lifted. The rule always has been in effect, but was interpreted by workers and managers to mean that construction crews could work below a floor that was fastened. <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> officials previously assumed that a permanent floor above the workers would break the fall of a higher concrete floor that slipped and fell. Other portions of the new rules would require that a `` qualified designer'' design lift-slab projects. Also, the rules say that all jacks lifting the floors should be able to lift 2.5 times the weight expected to be applied and all slabs should be lifted in a level position.
