</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON> said Friday the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> should use fewer consultants, but he strongly defended his tenure against criticism arising from the current <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> bribery investigation. `` The changes that we made in the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> procurement system were deep and fundamental,'' <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` I do not believe that any of the changes that we made could by their nature increase the incidence of improper behavior.'' <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON> resigned last year after leading the naval build-up that was a key part of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s defense program. But the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> is now the center of a bribery investigation by federal prosecutors, who are looking at allegations of payoffs and bribes from consultants, many of whom were former <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> employees. The consultants were seeking information from <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials about details of contracts, information that could make the difference in winning multi-million dollar contracts. No charges have yet been filed. A key figure of the investigation is <PERSON> Melvyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON>, the former assistant <ORGANIZATION> navy </ORGANIZATION> secretary for research and engineering and a close associate of <LOCATION> Lehman </LOCATION> during their <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> tenure. <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON> resigned and became a high-priced consultant shortly after <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON> quit to take a Wall Street job in April, 1987. <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON>'s testimony to the committee was his first major public comment since the investigation became public three months ago. <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON> declined to talk about details of the investigation and committee members did not ask him for specifics because they did not want to affect the probe. <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON> noted the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has more consultants than the other services, chiefly because the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has fewer officers. Consultants do work for the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> performed by officers in the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, he said. But `` I was never comfortable with the dependence on consultants,'' <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON> said, detailing what he said were generally unsuccessful efforts to reduce the number of consultants. `` Consultants are essential, but we do have too many,'' he said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> could substantially reduce its reliance on consultants.'' Two reforms suggested in the wake of the investigation are requiring consultants to register, and requiring them to disclose all their contracts to prevent conflicts of interest. <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON> endorsed those changes. The combative former official also strongly defended changes he made during his tenure. Some critics have suggested the changes, such as more centralized management and elimination of some layers of bureaucracy, caused the climate which led to the investigation. `` With regard to strong centralized policy-making, and decentralized execution, I see no way that either principle increases the opportunity for waste, fraud and abuse,'' he said. `` I am very proud of the achievements made in rebuilding the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> during my tenure,'' he said. `` I do believe the changes that led to that success made the system by its nature more susceptible to waste, fraud, and abuse.'' Overall, said <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON>, the Pentagon should be reorganized to give much more authority for daily decisions to lower-level personnel, rather than top officials. He opposed the creation of a single purchasing `` czar,'' a change proposed by some legislators. `` In rough book value, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> equals the top 30 companies on the Fortune 500 list combined,'' he said. `` And yet the Pentagon is organized in theory like a small business, with all operational authority and decision-making drawn up in one centralized office.'' He proposed that the secretary of defense simply make policy, and turn all other major decisions over to the three services. The staff should also be reduced by half, he said, and that goal could be easily achieved. `` Normal attrition in the military and civil service is about 8 percent per year, so careful use of hiring freezes brings a rapid natural shrinkage,'' he said. `` Increased opportunity for voluntary early retirement with pensions or large severance payments would enable a new administration to cut the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> bureaucracy by 30 percent in three years without firing a single person.''
