<HEAD>Bush Attacks Show Weaknesses And Strengths Of Dukakis Economic
Record</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s assault on <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' fiscal record renews a debate over statistics that are generally favorable to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> but show some holes in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>' economic rebound. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> struck at the heart of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' candidacy _ his stewardship of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> during its economic boom _ with a speech Thursday that selectively used statistics to point out chinks in the state financial record but that also gave a misleading characterization of the state's tax picture. `` You can pretty much do what you want with selected statistics,'' said <PERSON> Betsy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodeling </PERSON>, spokeswoman for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' Department of Revenue `` If you wanted to call day night you could probably find a statistic to support that.'' An obvious example is jobs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> cited the state's loss of 26,000 manufacturing jobs since 1983. State officials have put the number closer to 100,000 but they also cite a net gain of more than 400,000 jobs since 1983. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> spending increased between 1983 and 1987 at a rate faster than any other state, and that tax increases in that period were second only to <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> administration officials did not dispute <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s assertion on spending State budgets have grown by nearly $ 1 billion a year since 1983, fueled by soaring state revenues. Much of the increased spending has been in the form of aid to cities and towns hurt by a voter-approved property tax cap and the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's decision to halt revenue sharing with municipalities. On the tax side, however, administration officials denounced <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s figures, which do not take into account the record increase in per-capita income in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> over the four-year period the vice president cited. During that period state taxes have been cut several times, including the repeal of a surtax <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> authored in 1975, his first year as governor. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> initially opposed most of the tax cuts. `` -LRB- <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> -RRB- chose the per capita figures because they appear to show that taxes went up,'' said <PERSON> Hodeling </PERSON>. `` What they fail to show is that people here are making a lot more money so of course they are paying more taxes. Percentage-wise, taxes have been cut.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> cited the surtax to support his position that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was the biggest tax raiser in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> history; <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> sought the increase to erase a $ 600 million deficit inherited from his Republican predecessor. `` There are probably a zillion ways to measure taxes,'' said <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Republican Leader <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>, who met with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in July to discuss state finances. `` In any political campaign you have charges and countercharges and statistics can be used to support a variety of things.'' The vice president chided <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for approving $ 7.4 billion in long-term borrowing for capital projects during his tenure and for not fully funding the state's pension system. However, Wall Street's two major bond rating agencies recently termed <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>' long-term debt moderate compared to many states and said its economy appeared strong enough to support the debt. And it was <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> who last year convinced the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> to pass a plan to fund the pension system, an effort which he had made a priority in his second and third terms. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> did tap into surplus pension funds this year to help offset a $ 450 million revenue shortfall. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also asserted that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has turned a state surplus into a deficit that could grow to $ 700 million by the end of the current fiscal year. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> last year won passage of about $ 180 million in new taxes and cut state spending by more than $ 200 million to end fiscal 1988 with a $ 67 million surplus and to support revenue projections in the current budget. Many legislators, most of them Republicans, have predicted the state will fall short of money again this year but even <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' harshest critics say it is too early to make a credible assessment `` I personally think $ 700 million is a reasonable estimate but you ca n't prove it,'' said <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, executive director of <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Limited </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taxation </ORGANIZATION> and a <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> enemy. `` Nobody can prove it. But candidates snipe at each other.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has stood behind his revenue projections but has promised to cut spending if necessary. He was forced into that position last year and the state has had to borrow on a short-term basis for the first time since 1980, issuing more than $ 1 billion in notes in the past eight months to pay its bills. That will cost taxpayers about $ 20 million in interest payments.
