<TEXT>
 The Vietnamese government has agreed to a joint effort to find the remains of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> servicemen missing in action during the Vietnam War, the administration announced Friday. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said the investigation will focus on seven cases in which there is evidence that the victims were alive at the time they came under Vietnamese custody. At the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said the seven are part of the 70 `` most compelling cases'' which <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials raised with Vietnamese authorities last year. Other officials said that that although the 70 were presumed to be alive when captured, all have long since been presumed dead because there is no evidence to prove otherwise. A 90-day period, beginning Sept. 1, was set aside for carrying out the investigations, <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said, with each one limited to 10 days. About 2,400 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> servicemen have been listed as missing in action in <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> announced the agreement with <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> during a POW-MIA Recognition Day ceremony on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. House Republican Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> urged the families of the missing Americans to ignore the rumors that will be inevitable during the pending search. `` We have to continue to press for an accounting of each and every one, even though the prospects of finding anyone alive diminish with the passing of time,'' <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> told the crowd of several hundred. `` We must continue to seek the truth,'' he said. `` But the two greatest enemies of truth are rumors and false hopes. Nothing could be more cruel to the families of MIAs and POWs than to lend credence to false rumors, to raise hopes without the facts to support them, to muddy the waters and confuse the issue.'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said he was encouraged by recent agreements between Vietnamese Vice Premier <PERSON> Nguyen </PERSON> <PERSON> Co </PERSON> <PERSON> Thach </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s special POW-MIA emissary to <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>, Gen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vessey </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> `` Although last month <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> temporarily suspended its offer to conduct joint operations, it recently agreed to resume cooperation, and I am pleased to announce that joint activity will begin on Sept. 25,'' the secretary said <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION> has agreed to similar efforts, `` but we still await the results that we know are possible from those who hold the answers,'' he said. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> called on <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> to repatriate remains it claims to hold and criticized the government of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> for failure to return those of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> forces missing in the Korean War. `` The <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION> have a golden opportunity this year to display their willingness to rejoin the real world by dealing in good faith through the proper channels on this vital human issue,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republican Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, who joined <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> in addressing the crowd. `` Let's hope that when we meet again next year, we can report real progress and real results,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said. `` The bottom line is: We'll never forget, and we'll never give up.'' As part of the day of remembrance, wreath-laying ceremonies were being held at the <ORGANIZATION> Arlington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cemetery </ORGANIZATION> in honor of POWs and MIAs from the Korean War. An organization dedicated to remembering the families of missing soldiers, No Greater Love, estimates that there are 8,100 MIAs and 389 POWs still unaccounted for in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. An estimated 79,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> servicemen were missing in action in World War II.
