<HEAD>Three Generations Of Wyeth Family Art Comes Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE RULE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHADDS FORD, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An exhibit of three generations of <PERSON> Wyeth </PERSON> family art was staged in palaces and ultramodern museums during its world tour, but <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyeth </PERSON> says the works look best hanging in his hometown. The exhibition of 115 works by <PERSON> N.C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyeth </PERSON>, his son <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> and his grandson <PERSON> James </PERSON> opens Sunday in <LOCATION> Brandywine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Museum </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Chadds </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ford </LOCATION>. It is the final stop of a 1 -LCB- - year tour that also included stops in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> <PERSON> James </PERSON> until recently has answered to the family nickname of <PERSON> Jamie </PERSON>. But he now wants to be known as <PERSON> James </PERSON>. Speaking at a press preview Friday, he said, `` I've seen the paintings hanging in a czarist building in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> ... in a ultramodern museum in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> ... in an old-style building in <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> -RRB-, but it still looks a hell of a lot better here at home.'' <PERSON> Chadds </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, southwest of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, is where <PERSON> N.C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyeth </PERSON> settled after traveling through the Old West during the late 1800s and early 1900s. <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> were raised here, and many of their works explore the people and surroundings. Other works examine the people and atmosphere of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, where the family has a second home. The most celebrated <PERSON> Wyeth </PERSON>, 71-year-old <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON>, was scheduled to attend the press preview, but a touch of the flu and a `` drained'' feeling he gets when he completes a work caused him to stay away Friday, his son said. Through the worldwide tour, people flocked to the exhibit in record-breaking numbers to get a glimpse of art that explores such American traditions and lifestyles as farming and Halloween. But the collection also shows the enduring tradition of an artistic family, and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyeth </PERSON> said that is what appealed most to the exhibit's audiences abroad. `` It was the continuity that really struck them,'' he said. The exhibit opened in <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> in March 1987 and was the first exhibit under the newest cultural exchange program between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` The people were really dying to see the art,'' he said. `` At some openings, people just stand around with their backs to the paintings, but there they were almost pushing me aside to see the paintings.'' Included in the exhibit are three of <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyeth </PERSON> famous `` Helga'' paintings, a series of nudes and other figure studies of the same woman that caused a sensation when its existence was disclosed two years ago. When asked if he had any secret paintings, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyeth </PERSON> laughed. `` Yes, of a lot of pigs,'' he said. He posed for photographs before one of his more famous works, Portrait of a Pig, a 4-by-7-foot painting done in 1970. The pig is one of his favorite subjects and the exhibit displays several paintings of other farm animals as well. The first portion of the exhibit displays <PERSON> N.C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyeth </PERSON>'s art. Although there are several paintings of Western scenes and a small self-portrait from 1913, the majority of the 38 works on display are book illustrations. <PERSON> N.C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyeth </PERSON>, who died in 1945, illustrated such classics as <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON>'s `` Treasure Island'' and `` Kidnapped,'' and <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Twain </PERSON>'s `` The Mysterious Stranger'' in the 1910s and 1920s. The exhibit runs through Nov. 20.
