<HEAD>NHTSA Probes Allegations of Chrysler, Nissan Seat Defects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal regulators opened an investigation into reports that defective seats on more than 3 million Chrysler and <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> vehicles can cause drivers to lose control, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said Friday. The agency also opened 10 other preliminary evaluations, the lowest level of investigation, into alleged automotive defects. Seat backs on 1.5 million <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> cars and 1.7 million Chrysler Caravan and Voyager vehicles allegedly are prone to collapse suddenly, jarring the driver and causing him or her to steer out of control, according to unconfirmed reports received by <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION>. The agency ordered preliminary evaluations of all <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> passenger vehicles made from 1982 through 1984 and all 1984-1987 Chrysler Caravan and Voyager models. <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> said it has received 17 complaints of seat-back failure in the <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> vehicles, allegedly resulting in four accidents in which five people were injured. Nine complaints received by the agency involved the Caravan and Voyager. There was allegedly one accident in which three people were injured, <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> said. `` We are aware of the <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> investigation and have received the inquiry,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Cervone </PERSON>. `` We are investigating the claim ourselves and will cooperate fully with <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION>'s investigation.'' <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> U.S.A. </LOCATION> said it would have no immediate comment. Four new investigations involved other major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automakers. The agency was studying allegations of door-hinge pin failure on <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s 1987-88 Beretta and <LOCATION> Corsica </LOCATION> models, and a <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> service bulletin reporting erratic cruise-control response on the company's 1988 G vans with 6.2-liter diesel engines. <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> also opened probes of alleged failure of a seat-belt clip in <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s 1984 Mustang and floormat interference with the accelerator in the company's 1987-1988 Thunderbird and Cougar cars. Other new investigations ordered by <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> involved: _ Steering shaft separation in the 1986 <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Excel </ORGANIZATION>, in reaction to a Canadian recall _ Ruptured fuel hoses in <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> Excels, in reaction to an Australian recall _ Brake light switch failure in the 1985 BMW 325, 524, 528, 535, 635 and 735 models _ Heater core ruptures in the 1987 <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Golf </ORGANIZATION> _ Failure of some truck tires made by Danubian _ Brake shoe and caliper failure in some Midas products
