<HEAD>Couple Spends Honeymoon With Gilbert</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hurricane Gilbert</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A honeymoon in paradise turned into a nightmare for newlyweds who wound up sharing their closet with another couple as a shelter against the fury of Hurricane <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>. `` Next time we're going to the -LRB- <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> -RRB- <PERSON> Dells </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON>, 23, who returned from <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Green </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> on Thursday with his wife, <PERSON> Vicky </PERSON>, 23. `` It was frightening, and very sad,'' <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> said. `` It made us sick to our stomachs. Those people did n't have much to live in before. And the people who run the shops ... well, the tourists are their life.'' The Charleses, both registered nurses at <ORGANIZATION> Bellin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, flew out of <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> on one of the first commercial flights leaving the vacation island. The Bellevue couple had flown to <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> on Sept. 7, four days after their wedding. They stayed at a hotel about 10 miles up the coast from <LOCATION> Montego </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> said he was reassured by hotel officials Sunday night that the weather would n't be a problem. `` When we woke up Monday morning, there was a note under our door that a hurricane was coming,'' he said. `` We were on the fourth floor and they moved us to the third floor. But we were never told anything the whole time.'' They spent Monday walking around the village. That day they saw a grass hut in front of the hotel blow away and decided to take cover. `` Another honeymoon couple hid in our closet and we got under the bed,'' <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> said. `` But then the glass started to crash and we got in the closet with them.'' They barricaded themselves with mattresses and stayed in the closet for almost two hours. `` Everything was shaking and we could hear the roof coming off,'' <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> said. `` Windows were crashing in and we had some water come under the closet door. It was frightening.'' The Charleses later offered their medical help to hotel officials. That night, they shared their room with eight people. The newlyweds had three choices of places to go for their honeymoon, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> said: `` <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Cayman </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cancun </LOCATION>.'' All three were hit by the hurricane.
