<HEAD>Farmers Offer To Take Additional 3.4 Million Acres From Production</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Farmers have offered to take an additional 3.4 million acres of highly erodible cropland from production under the 10-year Conservation Reserve Program, or <ORGANIZATION> CRP </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Friday. <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hertz </PERSON>, administrator of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stabilization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said the offers, or bids, were made in the seventh signup for the program held July 18 through Aug. 31. Under the program, farmers agree to take land from production for 10 years. In return, based on bids they submit, farmers get annual rental payments from the government and one-time assistance pay for half the cost of planting grass, trees and shrubs to guard against erosion. The annual rental payments have been averaging around $ 50 per acre. Acceptance of the bids will be announced around Dec. 15, <ORGANIZATION> Hertz </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in the 1985 farm law set a goal of 40 million to 45 million acres for the program by 1990. `` New CRP contracts may not be entered into which provide for an annual rental rate in excess of the prevailing local rental rate for comparable land,'' he said. `` Making this determination on each bid will require extra time.'' Including more than 25.5 million acres signed up earlier, the latest offers would boost the program to almost 29 million acres if all of the new bids are accepted. <ORGANIZATION> Hertz </ORGANIZATION> said he was encouraged by the continued interest in the <ORGANIZATION> CRP </ORGANIZATION>, particularly in view of the 1988 drought. <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>, senior associate of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, a private, non-profit research organization based in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, said the latest offerings were `` really a pretty amazing signup when it started at the worst of the drought.'' <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> said the signup could have turned out to be light, since crop prices were going up rapidly because of the drought and it would have been tempting for many farmers to think about growing crops instead. `` But a lot of them may have thought these high -LRB- commodity -RRB- prices are n't here to stay,'' <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> said. `` Also, the department raised the bid levels the Corn Belt, and that helped.''
