<TEXT>
 Criminal investigators are looking for a connection among three decapitated bodies of young men found since May in widely separated areas of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. The only current ties in the three deaths are that none of the bodies showed signs of a struggle and that they shared similar physical characteristics, officials said. The first was found in May near <LOCATION> Cartersville </LOCATION> in northwestern <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, the second Sept. 6 near <LOCATION> Warwick </LOCATION> in southern <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and the third Wednesday near <LOCATION> Bogart </LOCATION> in the northeastern part of the state. All three were missing hands and head, with one also missing his feet. None of the three has been identified, and officials have released no cause of death in any of the cases. `` There's no question, to find bodies like this in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> is very, very unusual,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bankhead </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigation </ORGANIZATION>. `` We're trying to see how they might be linked, but there's no way we can be sure if they are right now,'' he said. The bureau is checking with other states to see if there are similar cases. Local sheriffs said each man appeared be of average height, between 5-feet-6 and 6-feet, and of average build. Officials believe each man was killed elsewhere and then left where the bodies were found. Investigators hope they can find leads from the clothing found on the Bogart and <LOCATION> Bartow </LOCATION> bodies. The <ORGANIZATION> Warwick </ORGANIZATION> body was clad only in underwear.
