<HEAD>Region Comprised of Varied Economy, Topography</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> is an upside-down triangle of land stretching 250 miles southward from <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>. _ Geography: Dominated by flat, arid brushland that divides into palm tree-laden coastal plains to the east and the dusty <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> to the west A system of barrier islands, including <LOCATION> Padre </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Mustang </PERSON>, protects much of the coast. _ Culture: <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> is a mix of posh resorts and extreme poverty that maintains strong cultural ties with <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> _ Economy: Extreme <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> has some of the highest unemployment rates in the nation Major industries in the lightly populated area include agriculture, oil and natural gas drilling. The region is home to the famous King Ranch, larger than <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. The region also has many `` maquiladoras,'' or twin plants, where <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies manufacture products using less costly Mexican labor. In the <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION> <LOCATION> valley </LOCATION>, the economy is boosted by thousands of retirees who spend winter in the region. _ Cities: The largest city in the region south of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION> is <LOCATION> Corpus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Christi </LOCATION>, population 250,000 <LOCATION> Laredo </LOCATION>, a town of about 125,000 along the <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION>, is a major gateway for trade with <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. The delta of the <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION> includes the cities of <LOCATION> Edinburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> McAllen </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Har