<HEAD>Textile Lawmakers Keep Bill Out of Conference Committee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Textile-state lawmakers won a key tactical victory Friday in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, persuading a committee chairman to change course and push for approval of Senate-passed import legislation without any changes. `` In my opinion this will insure passage of the textile bill by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> this year,'' Sen. <PERSON> Strom </PERSON> <PERSON> Thurmond </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-S.C. </LOCATION>, said after receiving word of the decision. `` The biggest danger we face now is a presidential veto.'' The bill, designed to protect American manufacturers from foreign competition, would freeze current textile and apparel imports at 1987 levels and hold growth to one percent annually starting next year. Advancing amid a flurry of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration veto threats, the measure would also cap nonrubber footwear imports at 1987 levels with no provision for increases. <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, D-Ill., met for 45 minutes with 20 textile-state lawmakers and then consulted with senior committee members before deciding on an about-face that will avoid sending the bill to a <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> conference committee At <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>'s urging, the committee had approved Wednesday a plan to send the bill to a conference committee with the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to resolve differences. Textile lawmakers said the measure could become snagged in the conference committee. House Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, told reporters Thursday that it was `` not certain'' that the measure would go to a conference committee. He indicated that there was still time to change course. The bill's supporters say it is needed to save American jobs that will inevitably dwindle as the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market becomes flooded with textile and apparel imports. Critics say the measure represents protectionism that would narrow consumer choices and actually cost more jobs than it would save when Asian textile-exporting nations retaliate. Congressional supporters of the textile industry expect <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to veto the legislation. He vetoed an earlier version in 1985. Thus far, industry supporters have been unable to muster the two-thirds support in either house needed to override a veto and pass the measure into law over the president's objections. At all costs, however, they hope to deny <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> the opportunity to exercise a so-called pocket veto. The president may prevent a bill from becoming law when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is out of session merely by refusing to sign it. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had set a target date for adjournment of Oct. 5, although that easily could be extended an extra week. Textile industry supporters say forcing <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to use his veto pen and not merely kill the bill with a pocket veto would exact a much higher political price from the Republican ticket in textile-producing states. Differences between the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill and the year-old <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> version are few. The House bill would freeze imports at 1986 levels. It would set up a one-year pilot program under which the government would auction off import licenses. It would guarantee better quotas to countries that increased their purchases of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm goods. And it would set up a special quota for imported silk neckties. Other than that, the two measures are the same.
