<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A jury decided Friday that <PERSON> Valerie </PERSON> <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> was right and <ORGANIZATION> Lorimar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telepictures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> was wrong in the dispute that ended her role in the `` Valerie'' television series, awarding her nearly $ 2 million in damages and a share of the profits. The jurors gave <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> and her husband, <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Cacciotti </PERSON>, who worked as a supervising producer for the show, $ 1.85 million in general damages. The jury found that <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> also is entitled to 12.5 percent of the adjusted gross profits of the series for the 1987-88 season _ even though she was no longer on the show for most of the season. The contract wold have run through 1991. Her lawyer estimated that her share of last season's profits could eventually amount to as much as $ 15 million if the show is syndicated. Jurors found that <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON> had acted with `` oppression and malice'' in firing her. But the jury declined to grant her and her husband any punitive damages. `` The television business is just like any other business,'' said jury foreman <PERSON> Archie </PERSON> <PERSON> McDaniels </PERSON>, a postal worker. `` You have good and bad. This verdict does n't condemn the TV industry. You just have to treat people fairly.'' Some of the jurors lined up in the hallway after delivering their verdict to get Miss <PERSON> Harper </PERSON>'s autograph. The actress, engulfed by well-wishers and reporters as she left the courtroom, said she felt `` vindicated.'' She said she hoped the decision will be `` a landmark in terms of how actors are dealt with.'' `` People have to be accountable for what they do,'' she said. `` That's the real victory in this case.'' <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON> attorney <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Engel </PERSON> called the verdict `` a mixed bag'' and said that from <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON>'s standpoint, `` it could have been worse.'' He said he was pleased that no punitive damages were awarded, and added that in a case that pitted an an individual against a big corporation, `` we did n't do so bad.'' He said an appeal was unlikely because `` the verdict is so small,'' but <ORGANIZATION> Lorimar </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Brogliatti </PERSON> said: `` We're disappointed in the verdict And our attorney has advised us there are grounds for an appeal and we are considering it.'' <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON> sued <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Harper </PERSON>, claiming she breached her contract by quitting the <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> show `` Valerie.'' A countersuit by <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> and her husband contended she was wrongfully fired from the show. <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON> offered extensive testimony depicting <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> as a temperamental star who wanted complete creative control. Miss <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> testified she wanted input on creative decisions but was not trying to wrest complete control. She had stressed that she brought the concept of the `` Valerie'' series to <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> and expected to help shape the episodes. She claimed the writers and producers changed the show to minimize her role and focus on the teen-age boys in the series. <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> replaced Miss <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> on the show, which was retitled `` The <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> Family.''
