<FIRST>r w AM-FuelEconomy     09-16 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fuel Economy,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Says EPA Need Not Recalculate Mileage Data</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court reversed two previous court decisions and let stand Friday changes the government imposed three years ago in the way automobile fuel economy is tested. Critics of the 1985 changes by the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> had charged that the changes had allowed automakers to save millions of dollars in penalties for failing to meet fuel economy standards. A three-judge panel and later the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> had ruled in favor of a suit filed by the Center for Auto Safety, challenging the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s 1985 decision, which eased methods used by automakers to determine gas mileage for each of their car models. Those tests are used to determine fleet-wide fuel economy figures that each automaker must meet under separate regulations. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> establishes the fleet average, and if an automaker does not meet the average and does not have credits from past years, it must pay a civil penalty. The full appeals court said Friday that the two previous rulings, in 1986 and last May, were in error. As a result, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> testing procedures imposed in 1985 will stand. The full, 11-member appeals court said that it had not been determined that the Center for Auto Safety had standing to challenge the regulatory change by the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>, noting that the court that issued the earlier decision had been sharply divided on that issue. The ruling last May in favor of the Center for Auto Safety suit came in a 5-5 vote. `` We now hold that as a majority of the ... court was unable to satisfy itself that the court had jurisdiction, the court should not have taken any affirmative action on the merits -LRB- of the case -RRB-,'' the court said Friday. The issue involves testing methods used by the automakers for determining the fuel economy of each car model. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> in 1985 agreed to allow a series of technical changes in those methods which critics said made it easier for the manufacturers to attain higher mileage figures and, in turn, made it easier to meet fleet-wide fuel economy requirements. As a result, the suit argued, manufacturers such as <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which were having difficulty meeting the fuel economy requirements anyway, saved millions of dollars in penalties. `` The effect of today's decision is to let <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> off the hook from having to pay any penalties for failing to comply with fuel economy standards in previous model years,'' said <PERSON> Cornish </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitchcock </PERSON>, an attorney for the Center for Auto Safety. The automakers welcomed the appeals court decision. `` It reinstates <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s original rule-making, which <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> believes did account for the effects of changing test procedures on our corporate average fuel economy,'' said <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Buist </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s automotive emissions and fuel economy office in <LOCATION> Dearborn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Noack </PERSON>, a Washington-based spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION>, said the company `` welcomed the decision'' but said it would have no effect on <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s fleet-wide fuel efficiency performance for 1988 through 1990 models Federal law requires a 27.5 miles per gallon fleet-wide fuel economy standards for 1989-90 model cars, but <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> has proposed lowering that to 26.5 mpg. It has lowered it to 26 mpg in each of the past three model years, arguing that consumer demand for large, less fuel efficient cars, make the 27.5 standard difficult for automakers to reach.
