<HEAD>Congressmen Ask EPA to Hold Off on Superfund Study</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sixteen congressional committee chairmen, subcommittee chairman and ranking Republicans asked the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> on Friday not to begin a major study of the `` Superfund'' toxic waste cleanup program so late in the administration. `` The agency should concentrate its full energy and resources on implementing'' amendments to the cleanup law passed in 1986 `` rather than on reopening many policy questions which were hotly contested during enactment and during reauthorization less than two years ago,'' the leaders wrote to <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>. `` Second, it is inappropriate to spend Superfund money to undertake a costly Superfund reauthorization study during the final days of this administration,'' the group said. The agency had planned to give the <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> $ 2.5 million for a study to define issues that should be dealt with in the Superfund program. Environmentalists had objected that such a study really should be done as part of the congressional work leading to renewal of the law in 1991. `` Any long-term Superfund study going beyond data gathering should be developed by the next administration,'' the chairmen said. <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> DeRemer </PERSON>, an aide to <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, said the agency had to study the letter before replying but it appeared that `` they have misunderstood some of the purposes of the study.'' He said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> wanted an examination of all hazardous waste issues, not just Superfund. He noted that <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, in a Thursday conversation with reporters, had said most Superfund issues could be characterized as both `` policy'' and `` implementation'' issues, such as the question of `` how clean is clean'' standards. In that conversation, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> noted, `` I have n't had anybody yet come to me and say, ` <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, this is a dumb idea.''' However, he said `` we probably wo n't'' proceed if environmental groups decline to serve on the study steering committee. `` The issues are going to be the same in any administration,'' <PERSON> DeRemer </PERSON> said. `` There is no reason to wait. Changes can always be made in the new administration.''
