<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Advocates for the homeless told a federal judge Friday that the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> violated the law by selling foreclosed homes to the highest bidder without determining whether they could be used by the homeless and low-income people. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON>, representing the coalition of advocates for the homeless, told <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Gasch </PERSON> that <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> receives 70,000 single-family houses each year _ about 7,000 a month _ but the agency `` can not proceed as if it is simply in the real estate business. They must consider the homeless.'' In a related case, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homeless </ORGANIZATION> also argued that the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has defied a congressional mandate to release underutilized federal property as housing for the nation's homeless. Ms. <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Foscarinis </PERSON>, a coalition attorney, said, `` There are thousands of properties underutilized which could be used for the homeless.'' She said that of the 12 facilities have been identified as underutilized by the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, only two have been made available to the homeless. Government attorney <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON> argued that the 1987 <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> McKinney </PERSON> Homeless Assistance Act _ named after the late <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> congressman who was a leading promoter of the measure _ does not apply to single-family dwellings. `` They want to shut down a program that has been going on for 50 years,'' <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON> said. `` They want to tie up the program.'' <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON>, another government lawyer, said all the agencies have complied with the provisions of the Homeless Act. `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was trying to match up the needs of the homeless with the properties available,'' he said. `` It is not a perfect match.'' <PERSON> Gasch </PERSON>, who heard three separate cases brought by homeless advocates against the government, took them under advisement, saying he would decide as soon as he can whether to issue preliminary injunctions. <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> told the judge that two temporary restraining orders issued last month preventing <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> from auctioning off its foreclosed single-family homes were to expire at the end of business Friday. <PERSON> Gasch </PERSON> merely said, `` I would hope they would maintain the status quo.'' <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> general counsel <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dorsey </PERSON> said the federal agency would follow the restraining order voluntarily until the end of business next Wednesday. It was anticipated that <PERSON> Gasch </PERSON> would decide the case by then. <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> has said that it generally sells the homes to the highest bidders _ frequently investors _ but insists that it has several programs designed to help homeless people find places to live. Recently, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> has been selling an average of 7,100 properties each month _ houses that had <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> mortgage insurance and that went into foreclosure when their owners could no longer keep up the mortgage payments. The program has produced some $ 2.4 billion in proceeds since Oct. 1, 1987, the start of the current fiscal year. <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> officials have argued that the court decisions, if upheld, could cost the agency $ 3 billion a year and bankrupt its single-family mortgage insurance fund. The <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, in a friend-of-the-court brief, said if <PERSON> Gasch </PERSON> issued an injunction, it would interfere with the orderly and efficient way <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> replenishes and restores the actuarial soundness of the <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> program. The association said it would reduce future refunds of premiums paid by current FHA-insured home owners, increase premiums of future <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> homeowners, `` make single-family programs unavailable or less attractive to prospective home buyers,'' and reduce the opportunities of home ownership for individuals and families in the future.
