<HEAD>Rains Drench Gulf States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Hurricane <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> pushed clouds and thunderstorms across the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> coast on Friday, pelting the area with rain and causing local flooding. Violent weather surrounding the hurricane spun off more than a half-dozen tornadoes in the <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, area Friday, blowing over at least two homes and slightly injuring one person. Thunderstorms related to <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> also spawned tornadoes Friday afternoon at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rucker </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Daleville </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>. Strong thunderstorm wind gusts caused damage to trees and house roofs at <LOCATION> Houma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La </LOCATION>. The calm eye at the heart of the hurricane made landfall about 120 miles south of <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION>, at 4:35 p.m. CDT, in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Tamaulipas </LOCATION> state The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said tides near the hurricane center will be as much as 11 feet higher than normal. <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> was expected to bring 10 to 15 inches of rainfall. By noon on Friday, showers and thunderstorms reached from eastern <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> across northern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and southern <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, western <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, northern <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>. Rain also continued over the northern <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. Rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p