<HEAD>Aquino Supporters Begin New Political Party</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf `But some...' with 3 grafs to ADD background.
PICKUP 9th pvs `Mrs. Aquino, who...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Supporters of President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> launched a new pro-administration political party Friday, but she said the move must not be allowed to divide democratic forces. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> hailed the formation of Struggle of the Democratic Filipino, the latest step in the realignment of forces that toppled President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' 20-year regime and propelled her to power in February 1986. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> made the remarks in a speech to the first national convention of the party. `` Perhaps it is time to have political parties,'' she said in a speech opening its first convention. `` Perhaps indeed, the time for realignment is now. Yet, I hope that these realignments do not portend the permanent and total division of the forces of democracy in our country. For should that happen, it will mean the end of all of us.'' She said divisions among pro-democracy Filipinos enabled <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, now in exile in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, to impose eight years of martial law in 1972 and prolong his rule. `` It is good for the country and for democracy if people with shared ideals and programs organize themselves into separate parties,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> said. `` But it would be disastrous if we divided ourselves again into permanent hostile camps.'' Rep. <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitra </PERSON>, speaker of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION>, was elected president of the new party, which organizers hope will bring together pro-government forces under a single banner and serve as the president's party. In February 1986 Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> ran for president under the banner of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> UNIDO </ORGANIZATION>, the party of her running mate, <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Laurel </LOCATION>. Since then, Vice President <PERSON> Laurel </PERSON> has criticized Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s policies, <ORGANIZATION> UNIDO </ORGANIZATION> has fared poorly at the ballot box and many of the party's legislators have defected to pro-Aquino parties. Last month Laurel formed an opposition movement, the Union for National Action. He accused Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> of incompetence and urged her to resign to make way for new elections but he received little popular support. Some pro-Aquino politicians say formation of the Struggle for the Democratic Filipino is a bid by the president's relatives and others to consolidate their own power before the 1992 presidential election. Among the party's main organizers is Rep. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Cojuangco </PERSON>, Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s influential younger brother. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, who has vowed not to seek re-election, told more than 5,000 delegates that she hoped the party was organized `` not only for the 1992 elections but to help our people face and overcome their problems.'' She said Filipinos were disenchanted with traditional political parties and the bickering and constant jockeying for positions. Political parties in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> traditionally revolved around personalities rather than ideology. <PERSON> Mitra </PERSON> said Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> avoided giving the party a ringing endorsement because she did not want to be accused of playing politics. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> said she was not favoring the party over other parties in the government coalition and would keynote their conventions if invited. <PERSON> Mitra </PERSON> said Thursday that the party was organized to consolidate political support for the government and establish a grass-roots, mass movement behind Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>. `` But there are others who do not believe in this thinking,'' <PERSON> Mitra </PERSON> said. He was referring to the refusal of 18 <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> members in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to join the new party. The Liberals, led by <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Jovito </PERSON> <PERSON> Salonga </PERSON>, are among six parties in the government coalition. But the Liberals have disagreed with other pro-government parties and with some of the president's influential relatives.
