ORGANIZATION>. Police officials said that once the investigation is completed, it is up to the state attorney to determine whether <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON> should stand trial. <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON> could face up to three years in prison for violating a 1986 law that bars Israelis from meeting with members of terror groups. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> considers the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> a terror group. <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON>, who made millions selling hamburgers in <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION> before becoming a peace activist, said he did n't think he broke the law because he met with <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> to promote peace. As <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON> arrived at the police station, about 20 members of the anti-Arab Kach movement waved an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> flag and shouted: `` A rope for the traitor.'' <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON> turned to the demonstrators and tapped his index finger against his temple to show he thought they were stupid. <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON> said he requested a meeting with Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> to brief him on what <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> said he would not see the activist, but told reporters one of his assistants might receive <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON>.
