<HEAD>Seoul Olympic Games Begin In Blaze of Pageantry</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: 23 grafs SUB for grafs 8-26 pvs, On Friday ... UPDATING with
new material on parade, other doings. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 1988 Summer Olympics, the largest and most tightly guarded in history, began in a blaze of pageantry Saturday as marchers in traditional Korean costumes entered the main stadium to the beat of a `` dragon drum.'' About 70,000 spectators in the Olympic Stadium and up to a billion television viewers around the world watched the spectacular show that began at 10:30 a.m. -LRB- 8:30 p.m. EDT Friday -RRB- in sunny weather. It was the first Olympic opening ceremony with a prelude outside the main stadium. Before the performances in the Olylmpic Stadium, a flotilla of 458 boats sailed by on the <LOCATION> Han </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> adjacent to the stadium. The theme of the three-hour extravaganza, with 13,000 performers, was `` Beyond All Barriers'' _ a phrase stressing the <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> Games as a stage for the first East-West competitions at the Summer Olympics in 12 years. Political boycotts had marred the 1980 <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Games and the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> competition four years ago. About 160 countries sent nearly 10,000 athletes to the Games to compete for 237 gold medals, making these 16-day Games the best-attended ever by competitors. South Korean security forces ringing the stadium and on alert across the nation were on guard against terrorism. Officals called the measures the most extensive ever to protect a sports event. <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> led the parade of teams, a tradition honoring the country as the site of the ancient Olympics. Teams marched according to the Korean alphabet, with <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION> second in the procession. As the host nation, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> was last. Most teams were garbed in matching jackets and pants or skirts, but African delegations wore native garb of flowing robes with colorful print patterns. The processions seemed less formal than at past Olympics opening ceremonies. Some teams broke ranks to wave to the cheering crowd. An <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> athlete carried a sign proclaiming, `` Hi, Mom, I'm Here. The teams gathered on the infield after circling the running track. The march route took them past the seating area for dignitaries, including South Korean President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo and <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Samaranch </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Olympic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Before the teams marched in, a chorus sang an ancient seafaring ballad, and thousands of blue and white balloons floated skyward. A replica of the huge dragon drum used in ancient Korean ceremonies was transfered from ship to shore then carried to the stadium. Huge balloons were released from a Shindan Tree, sacred in Korean mythology, and then the Olympic flame was revealed on a 72-foot pedestal resembling a traditional Korean candleholder. Korean dancers in Greek tunics and flowing gowns danced and whirled as silver-colored confetti rained down from the sky. `` I believe <PERSON> God </PERSON> is blessing my country for its years of hard work and preparation,'' said <PERSON> Yuk </PERSON> <PERSON> Hee-Jin </PERSON>, 17, a spectator. `` I'm really proud of my country The whole world will now know more about <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>.'' The opening ceremonies, as conceived, planned, practiced and practiced again, were designed by the Games' hosts to portray the Eastern philosophies of harmony and balance _ factors long-wanting in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s tumultuous history. Planners drew from the concept of <PERSON> Yin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Yang </PERSON>, the symbol on the <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> flag that is also a major Oriental philosophy. <PERSON> Yin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> represent opposing forces that come together in a bond of harmony and friendship. So the script for the Olympic opener mixed the Yin of the old and the Yang of the new. Music for the show came from ancient Korean drums and wind instruments as well as a synthesizer that pumped out modern pieces composed by contemporary Korean artists. The Koreans invited dancers from 60 nations to participate in the program of native dances from <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other nations. Music to accompany the marchers was composed from folk music of the various nations. The Koreans also sought to keep harmony among the nations marching in the opening ceremony. Plans to limit the number in the process were quickly scrapped after protests from several countries, including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. And while the program called for women in flowing white robes to march in front of the delegations carrying signs with each nation's name, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> was granted its wish that a man front their team because of the Moslem nation's strict fundamentalist tenets that forbid women from such public displays On Friday, a runner carried the Olympic torch to <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hall </ORGANIZATION> in a snowstorm of confetti, streamers and balloons. The torch relay began Aug. 23 in <LOCATION> Olympia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, site of the ancient Olympics. Elsewhere in the capital, hundreds of radicals staged anti-Olympic protests at three universities Friday. They burned the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flag and an effigy of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and yelled `` Down with the dictators' Olympics!'' Onlookers shouted at them as riot police watched from a distance. In the protests, radicals, some of them armed with firebombs and clubs, demanded the Olympics be shared with communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and charged the Games were being used to cement authoritarian rule in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> declared again Friday that the <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> government is using the Games to further divide the <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> peninsula. The two Koreas have been divided since the end of World War II and fought the Korean War in 1950-53.
