<HEAD>Norwegians in Dispute over Report that Seals are Skinned Alive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHAN RAPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A report that some hunters are skinning seals alive has touched off a bitter dispute in <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, where hunters and fishermen say seal killing is crucial to their way of life. Odd <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lindberg </PERSON>, an author and photographer who sailed as a government-appointed inspector on a hunting boat east of <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION> last spring, said in his report that seals were not only skinned alive but killed in deliberately `` sadistical ways.'' The report came as authorities sought to ease controls on seal killing, because fisherman complain that thousands of the animals have invaded <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s northern coast, eating fish and damaging nets. `` Since my report I have received at least 100 telephone threats, with some saying they are going to tear my limbs off,'' said <PERSON> Lindberg </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fisheries </ORGANIZATION>, which employed <PERSON> Lindberg </PERSON> to do the inspection, refuses to accept his report. `` It may be that he -LRB- <PERSON> Lindberg </PERSON> -RRB- believes he has seen things that he has not seen,'' said <PERSON> Trond </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Paulsen </PERSON>, a senior ministry official. The ministry has no plans to take action on his report, he said. But the report drew widespread sympathy for seals following a summer of death for the animals further south. A distemper virus killed 13,000 seals along the coasts of <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> since April. <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s leading newspaper, Aftenposten, devoted its front page to a color picture it said was taken by <PERSON> Lindberg </PERSON> of a seal pup in the water being clubbed with the blunt side of a long spiked pole. Killing pups in the water is prohibited, and it would appear from the photo that the hunter had apparently missed a clean kill on the head. In the 1970s, the French actress <PERSON> Birgitte </PERSON> <PERSON> Bardot </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Greenpeace </ORGANIZATION> and other environmental organizations successfully campaigned against seal slaughter here and in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. Their campaign led to a 1983 ban by the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> on imports of seal skins, a heavy blow to the seal hunters whose main market was the European fur industry. After the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> import ban, the <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> government banned the killing of seal pups, which are coveted for their white coats. <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s seal hunting fleet dwindled from about 50 vessels to five and the catch was cut from several hundred thousand seals a year to a quota of less than 40,000. However, disgruntled seal hunters now see the chance for a comeback. Later this year, the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> will start talks on the possibilities of either lifting the ban or making it permanent. A decision is expected next year. Last year's seal invasion softened public opinion in <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>. Fishermen complained they could lose their livelihoods if the seals were allowed to continue to eat their catch and destroy their nets. `` We count on the import ban being changed,'' said spokesman <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauritson </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fisheries </ORGANIZATION>. `` There are no logical, scientific grounds for it.'' <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> hunts seals during the spring in waters east of <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION> and in the <LOCATION> Barents </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, north of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lindberg </PERSON> was one of three inspectors assigned this year to make sure the killings were carried out according to detailed rules, intended to minimize the animals' suffering. He spent from mid-March to mid-April aboard a seal hunt vessel off <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lindberg </PERSON> said he turned in his report to the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fisheries </ORGANIZATION> at the beginning of July and that it created `` panic.'' `` The animals are rarely checked to see if they have been fatally shot,'' the report said, `` and are often alive when they are hoisted aboard. As a result it often happens that the animal is skinned while growling, its eyes pleading and its mouth snapping at you.'' He said he had seen animals that appeared to be dead but `` woke up'' while being skinned. Before releasing <PERSON> Lindberg </PERSON>'s report Sept. 2, the ministry issued a statement saying a committee of experts had found <PERSON> Lindberg </PERSON> `` not trustworthy.'' Other inspectors made no such complaints, said <PERSON> Paulsen </PERSON>. Officials said no formal qualifications are needed to be an inspector, but that they usually employ biologists, students and researchers. They said <PERSON> Lindberg </PERSON> had offered to do the job without pay. <PERSON> Lindberg </PERSON>, 43, has specialized in conditions for marine mammals in polar areas.
</TEXT>
