<HEAD>Nationalist Chinese Military Assailed as Too Powerful</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Nationalist Chinese military, long the backbone of the government, is under attack by critics who contend it remains too powerful at a time of easing tensions with rival communist <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Emboldened by the relaxed political atmosphere on <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> after nearly four decades of authoritarian rule, some Taiwanese claim the military abuses its power despite the lifting of martial law here a year ago. Newspapers, which customarily hushed up any allegations of military wrongdoing in the past, now give wide coverage to the charges of abuses. The Nationalist government and armed forces led by <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Kai-shek </PERSON> fled to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> in 1949 after losing a civil war to the communists on the mainland and remain technically at war with <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> still regards <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> as a renegade province but has not launched a significant military action since 1958, when communist forces fired hundreds of thousands of artillery shells at two tiny Nationalist-held offshore islands, <LOCATION> Quemoy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Matsu </LOCATION>. `` Soldiers used to be admired for defending the country with their lives,'' said legislator <PERSON> Chang </PERSON> <PERSON> Shih-liang </PERSON> of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. `` But with the absence of wars for so long, people began to question what they have been doing.'' A central figure in the controversy is <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s only four-star general, <PERSON> Hau </PERSON> <PERSON> Pei-tsun </PERSON>, head of the general chiefs of staff since 1981 and one of those who came to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> after the communists won the mainland in 1949. <PERSON> Hau </PERSON>, who commands <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s half a million troops, was praised for ensuring a peaceful transfer of power after the death in January of President <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Ching-kuo </PERSON>, the son of <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Kai-shek </PERSON>, who lifted martial law despite his strong ties to the military. But critics argue that <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Ching-Kuo </PERSON>'s successor, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Teng-hui </PERSON>, has little control over the armed forces, which are allocated an estimated 46 percent of <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s annual budget of nearly $ 20 billion. `` No military officers dared to give an order without the prior approval from <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Ching-kuo </PERSON>, but it appears no one can control them now,'' said <PERSON> Chang </PERSON> <PERSON> Chung-tung </PERSON>, history professor at <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taiwan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, a native Taiwanese, has yet to build up his own power base in the Nationalist military that remains dominated by officers who came from mainland <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. That also has led to speculation that <PERSON> Hau </PERSON>'s influence is growing. Some liberal newspapers and magazines recently criticized <PERSON> Hau </PERSON> on grounds that he promoted several of his own men, including two generals demoted by <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Ching-kuo </PERSON> for dereliction of duty. Newspapers also have suggested that <PERSON> Hau </PERSON> played an influential role in crafting the Nationalist party's new policy-making <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that was named in July. The military retained three of 31 committee seats, including one held by <PERSON> Hau </PERSON>. Opposition politicians have assailed the armed forces for their role in trying to crack down on dissent, claiming military police and intelligence agents have appeared at major anti-government demonstrations where only a police presence was appropriate. In August, several dozen members of the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> staged a protest in <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION> to demand the impeachment of <PERSON> Hau </PERSON> because a military jail burned the memoirs of a renowned dissident prisoner. The liberal <ORGANIZATION> Independence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evening </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said in an editorial July 27 that with the lifting of martial law `` we thought military personnel would reduce their role to that of defending the state and civilians.'' `` Rather, we saw the military openly intervening in political factional disputes, continuing to have a hand in social and economic affairs and having too much say in government personnel changes,'' it said. A <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Chang </PERSON> <PERSON> Hui-yuan </PERSON>, called the newspaper's accusations `` malicious slandering'' and `` an insult to our troops.'' To counter the intense criticism, the military has launched a campaign to stress the importance of national defense in speeches and through concerts, plays and television shows, including one showing the 69-year-old Hau swimming, golfing and playing with his grandson. In a speech marking Soldiers' Day on Sept. 3, <PERSON> Hau </PERSON> urged Taiwanese `` not to reduce the sense of crisis while living in comfort,'' claiming that communist <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> still could invade <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> at any time. Professor <PERSON> Chang </PERSON> reflects widespread sentiment when he labels as unlikely the possibility of a military coup or a military-led campaign to reverse the recent liberalization trend that has permitted political opposition and relaxed unofficial ties with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. `` Military officers must have realized that the public would not support them in case of a coup,'' he said. `` They must also ask whether they could control the troops before moving to seize power.'' Most of the troops are native Taiwanese, who make up 85 percent of the island's population.
