<HEAD>Accident Led to Many Changes in Ranks at NASA; Astronauts Now in
Charge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Almost all the men who ignored the warnings and gave the go-ahead for the Challenger launch are gone and new ones are in place as the shuttle program returns to flight. One shuttle astronaut, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Truly </PERSON>, now is at the helm of <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s spaceflight program. Another, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Crippen </PERSON> _ who has been on four shuttle missions _ will give the final nod to commit Discovery and other future shuttles to flight. The top officials of <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION>, which built the booster rocket that doomed the Challenger, are gone. Gone, too, is most of the <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> hierarchy, and gone are the directors of <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> centers investigated by the presidential Challenger commission. There are two notable exceptions: <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Aldrich </PERSON>, one of the <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> bosses who gave final approval for the Jan. 28, 1986, flight, and <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> engineer who argued against the launch but was overruled. <PERSON> Aldrich </PERSON> is director of the shuttle program at <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> headquarters and <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION> is in charge of <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION>'s space operations The <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION> commission presented its conclusion that Challenger `` was an accident rooted in history,'' but it did not recommend any criminal indictment. Still, Sen. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON>, D-S.C. demanded that `` every single person be identified and disciplined.'' That seems to have been done without resorting to the courts. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulloy </PERSON>, former manager of the booster rocket program at the Marshall Space Flight Center who had brushed off the Thiokol concerns, and <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Reinartz </PERSON>, manager of shuttle projects who decided not to tell top launch officials about those concerns, both left <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>. So has <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON>, the <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> official who told <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> he was `` appalled'' at the firm's original recommendation that the launch should not take place. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> was working without its chief on the day of the tragedy, and the man with the title of acting administrator was new to the agency. Administrator <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Beggs </PERSON> had stepped aside in early December 1985 when he was indicted on charges unrelated to <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>. Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, who had been deputy administrator for only 10 days when <PERSON> Beggs </PERSON> stepped out, had to take the heat for the worst tragedy in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s space program. After Challenger, <PERSON> Beggs </PERSON> resigned and <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> remained as acting administrator until Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> returned in May 1986 from private life and reassumed the job of administrator he had held for eight years in the 1970s. `` Where management is weak, we will strengthen it,'' he promised. `` Where engineering or design processes need improving, we will improve it. Where our internal communications are poor, we will see that they get better.'' The purge had begun much earlier. The first to step down after Challenger was <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, assistant <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> administrator for spaceflight, who had already been named to take over as director of the <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. Truly was summoned from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> to take charge; he proclaimed `` the <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> can-do spirit is intact'' and quickly set out a conservative agenda to get back into the spaceflight business. In the <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> structure, center directors wield considerable power and those directly concerned with shuttle flight were quick to fall. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> remained at Johnson only a few months and left to take an ill-defined headquarters job that lasted six months. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> left the <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> for a private space firm. Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> retired from the <ORGANIZATION> Marshall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, which has charge of <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> propulsion systems and received the most criticism from the <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION> commission. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> went to the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> for Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> McCartney </PERSON> to head the Kennedy Space Center. At <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Aaron </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> was moved up and <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> got <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, a veteran space engineer, who came back to <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> from <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION>'s Plasma Physics Laboratory. Three of the four <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> officials who overruled their engineers and acceded to the Challenger launch still are with the company but in non-shuttle positions. They are <PERSON> J.C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kilminster </PERSON>, now in the automotive products division, <PERSON> R.K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lund </PERSON>, vice president of advanced technology; and <PERSON> Calvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiggins </PERSON>, general manager of the <LOCATION> Huntsville </LOCATION> division. <PERSON> Jerald </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, boss of the booster division, retired early. <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> engineer, said the company harassed him for his strong testimony before the <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION> commission and sued <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> for billions of dollars. The case was dismissed and he has left the company long ago.
