<SECOND>PM-Fuel Spill, Bjt,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Indicts Ashland Oil In Fuel Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> officials have reacted bitterly to criminal charges lodged against the company for a massive oil spill, saying the charges will impair efforts to comply with environmental laws. `` The company is disappointed that criminal actions will be pursued in light of <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION>'s efforts to mitigate the spill's impact and the fact that the company quickly accepted responsibility for the incident,'' <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Schrum </PERSON> said Thursday On Thursday, a federal grand jury indicted <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> for violations of the federal Clean Water and the Refuse acts, the first criminal charges arising from the Jan. 2 spill that contaminated drinking water in three states. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said the two misdemeanor counts were the most stringent that could be brought because federal environmental laws do not contain felony provisions for corporations for such offenses. `` We're doing the best we can,'' he said. `` We're following the evidence based on the law that exists here.'' Conviction carries a maximum penalty of a $ 200,000 fine on each count or double the monetary loss suffered as a result of the criminal conduct. So far, the losses amount to more than $ 10 million, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Schrum </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> voluntarily has paid more than $ 11.4 million for clean-up costs and to reimburse claims from individuals, businesses and government agencies. The decision to prosecute <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> goes against past practices by the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to pursue criminal violations only in instances of deliberate acts, he said. `` We think such actions impair rather than promote environmental compliance,'' <PERSON> Schrum </PERSON> said. The spill occurred when an <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> riverside storage tank at the company's Floreffe terminal in <LOCATION> Jefferson </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, collapsed while being filled with 3.8 million gallons of fuel oil. About 1 million gallons escaped the containment dikes at the facility, and more than 700,000 gallons spilled into the <LOCATION> Monongahela </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and traveled downstream, well beyond the river's confluence with the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> The government said the accident represented one of the largest inland oil spills in the nation's history, affecting drinking water supplies and plant and animal life in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. About 23,000 suburban <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> residents went without tap water for almost a week. The indictment said <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> had disassembled a 48-year-old oil storage tank near <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> in 1986 and then reassembled it at the <LOCATION> Floreffe </LOCATION> terminal. It was placed in service in August 1987. In May, investigators for an independent research institute that studied the accident said a dime-size flaw in the tank's brittle steel walls caused the collapse. Aggravating the condition were the relative weakness of the World War II-era steel, pressure from the diesel fuel and cold weather, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Battelle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. Besides failing to obtain all necessary local permits for erecting the tank, <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> said it failed to fill the tank with water before use, a test recommended by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, an industry group. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said the indictment does not end the federal government's investigation of the oil spill. He said the government still must determine if any <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> employees or officials violated the law. The state attorney general's office also is conducting a criminal investigation but has brought no charges. In a separate civil action in July, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> filed a proposed consent decree requiring <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Ashland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, to complete the clean-up of the spill and to reimburse the government $ 680,000 for emergency response work by federal agencies. <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to the decree's terms.
