<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has set the stage for two key votes that could remove the final regulatory obstacles in the <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION>, plant's long road toward a low-power operating license. If the <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> acts today in favor of the plant, <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> could be eligible for the license within 30 days, but <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> officials have vowed to fight the license in federal court. The low-power license has been a key pressure point in the struggle between <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> owners, the nuclear industry and <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION> state officials on one side and <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, local officials and anti-nuclear activists on the other. <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> must obtain the license, which would allow it to test the reactor at 5 percent of capacity, before securing a full-power commercial operating license. The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> is to decide two issues. The first is whether to allow a reactor to operate at low power without having an emergency system in place to alert neighbors in case of a plant accident. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> municipalities in the 10-mile zone forced <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> officials to remove the sirens. Under the new rule, the siren system would have to be in place only for full-power license consideration. <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> officials are working on plans to mount sirens on trucks and helicopters. The second issue, which was tentatively scheduled for an <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> vote, was a petition by opponents urging the commission to break from its regulations and consider the financial condition of the plant's owners. The lead owner, <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION>, filed for bankruptcy protection in January. <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> owns 36 percent of the plant. In June, <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wholesale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which is the fourth largest <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> shareholder at 12 percent, announced it was withdrawing from the project and would stop making its $ 2 million-a-month payments. For opponents, blocking the low-power license is critical because they say 5 percent power tests would contaminate the facility with radioactive fuel, ruling out a future conversion to a gas-fired plant or other facility advocated by nuclear critics. Plant officials say the tests would not rule out a conversion. <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> opponents believe plant owners and the commission are trying to win low-power license approval before the possibility of encountering a <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> presidency that could further hinder the licensing process. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the Democratic presidential nominee, says it would be impossible to quickly evacuate residents from the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> seacoast towns that lie within the plant's 10-mile emergency evacuation zone, an area that swells with summer tourists and has congested roads on normal days. The idle $ 5.6 billion reactor is losing $ 50 million each month in maintenance and finance costs. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> said last week that if the two regulatory obstacles were removed by the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGAN