<HEAD>Government, Farmers Denounce U.S. Rice Millers' Petition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Government officials vowed Friday that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> will not open its market to foreign rice imports, and expressed hopes the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will reject a petition from <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> rice farmers seeking to sell in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. `` Rice should be a serious concern to all Japanese,'' <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Eiichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakao </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> meeting Friday. `` Every Cabinet member should take this matter seriously and protect domestic rice production.'' <PERSON> Nakao </PERSON>'s remarks were quoted in a statement from the agency. The agriculture minister and other officials expressed regret at a complaint filed with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative's office Wednesday by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Millers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The organization, which represents 11,000 American rice growers, demanded that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> allow foreigners to provide 10 percent of its annual rice consumption of 10 million tons within four years. The petition was based on a section of the recently passed omnibus trade law, which requires the president to retaliate against a country deemed protectionist by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The Trade Representative's office has 45 days to decide whether to accept the petition before it starts investigations. `` The two governments have agreed not to negotiate this matter on a bilateral basis,'' Agricultural Minister <PERSON> Takashi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sato </PERSON> said at a news conference. `` We regret such a complaint was filed in spite of the agreement.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Rice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Millers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> filed a similar complaint in 1986, but it was turned down. <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> has sought arbitration at the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, an international body that governs world trade. Self-sufficiency in rice production is a sensitive issue in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, where rice remains the staple food. Rice growers comprise nearly 80 percent of all Japanese farmers.
