<HEAD>Annual Rate Rises to 5.7 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s annual rate of inflation rose to 5.7 percent in August, the highest level in three years, the government announced Friday. Nevertheless, the increase from 4.8 percent in July was not as bad as some investors and economists had feared. Stocks showed little reaction. Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> warned on Wednesday that there would be a significant increase in the rate because of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s practice of including mortgage rates in the calculation. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s mortgage rates have climbed sharply, and are in 13-percent range, following the government's move in recent months to push interest rates up to curb inflation by dampening the country's strong consumer spending. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s annual inflation rate has climbed substantially so far this year and is much higher than had been forecast. The rate stood at 3.3 percent in January.
