<HEAD>30,000 GM Trucks, Vans and School Buses Recalled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is recalling about 30,500 cars, trucks, vans and school buses to conduct safety-related inspections and replace parts that could be defective. The company said Thursday that about 8,000 1988 Buick Regals are being recalled for inspection and possible replacement of a brake hose that could wear through and result in a reduction of braking capability. About 21,000 1985 and 1986 Chevrolet and GMC P-30 trucks and G-30 vans also are being recalled to repair a control arm in the front suspension. The arm could crack, resulting in a loss of steering control, the company said. In addition, 1,500 1987 and 1988 model Chevrolet and GMC school buses, all equipped with gasoline engines, are being recalled because of possible problems in the location of air brake lines. The lines may have been put too close to exhaust systems, causing wearing and a partial or complete loss of brakes, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> said.
