<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, followed by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, leads the way in exporting substandard goods to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government agency responsible for inspecting foreign shipments said Friday. An official of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Import </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Export </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodities </ORGANIZATION> said 37.5 percent of 584 Italian products inspected in the first half of this year failed to meet contract standards either in quality or quantity. He said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was second-worst with 30.87 percent, or 517 of 1,675 shipments checked, of poor quality. The official, who was not identified, was quoted by the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION>. There was no elaboration on the type of shoddy goods shipped or which foreign trading partner had the best record. The report said 26.25 percent of British commodities, 24.73 percent of French products and 22 percent of goods from <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Macao </LOCATION> failed to meet contract standards. In total, the administration inspected 56,695 shipments of imported goods in the first half of the year, and found quality products in 15.7 percent. Serious problems also existed in motor vehicles imported from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> European countries, the report said. In the past, foreign businessmen accused of selling defective merchandise to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> have complained that their goods were damaged by mishandling or long delays in transport within <LOCATION> China </LOCATION