<FIRST>u f PM-BusinessInventories 2ndLd-Writethru   09-16 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Inventories, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Business Inventories Up Slightly</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS 3rd graf, The July, to reflect revisions, July
inventory rise now smallest since August 1987; CORRECTS 5th graf,
The July, to show that with revisions sales drop first since
November</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Business inventories rose only a modest 0.3 percent in July even though sales were down by 0.2 percent, the government said today. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said inventories held on shelves and backlots rose $ 2.2 billion to a seasonally adjusted $ 733.7 billion, while sales edged down by $ 1.2 billion. The July gain in inventories followed a 0.8 percent rise in June and was the 19th consecutive month without a decline. However, the July increase was the smallest since a 0.2 percent rise in August 1987. Economists sometimes take rising inventories as a sign of economic weakness. Too many goods in reserve could lead to production cuts and layoffs at manufacturing plants. However, analysts have not been worried over the past year because the inventory gain has simply been keeping up with strong sales. The July drop in sales was the first since November and followed a strong jump of 1.4 percent in June. The June inventory accumulation was led by 0.5 percent increases at both the manufacturing and wholesale levels. Inventories shrank by 0.1 percent at the retail level, where sales have been weakest in recent months. In sales, a 0.9 percent decline at factories more than offset a 0.6 percent rise at the wholesale level and a slight 0.1 percent increase at retail stores. An advance estimate of retail sales for August, released Thursday, showed a 0.2 percent decrease. The combination of weak sales and slowly rising inventories left the inventory-to-sales ratio unchanged at 1.5 in July. That means it would take 1.5 months to exhaust inventories at the July sales pace, a ratio not considered abnormally high.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
