<HEAD>Business Inventories Up, Sales Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites thruout with business inventories. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The government disclosed new evidence of a weakening economy today, reporting a rise in business inventories last month that coincided with a decline in sales. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said business inventories rose 0.3 percent in July while sales fell 0.2 percent. The July increase in inventories was the 19th straight month without a decline. The drop in sales was the first since January and followed a strong jump of 1.4 percent in June. Economists sometimes interpret rising inventories and slowing sales as a signal of economic weakness. Too many goods in reserve could lead to production cuts and layoffs at manufacturing plants. The report came a day after the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said sales of retail merchandise, a narrower category of sales, fell 0.2 percent in August, and the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry's operating rate was unchanged in August, the first time in six months the figure has n't increased These figures also suggested that the economy is beginning to weaken after a period of strong growth, thereby easing some fears of inflation that have dogged the nation's financial markets for months. The Federal Reserve, in an effort to slow the economy by curbing domestic demand, has been pushing interest rates higher since late March and economists say the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> tightening may be beginning to take hold. `` I think things are looking just fine inflation-wise,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> Evans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> consulting firm. `` I think the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> deserves an A. I think they tightened just enough to slow down the economy without sending it into a tailspin.'' Financial markets today showed little reaction to the economic news, however. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks had moved less than a point higher by late morning. In the bond market, prices were little changed, and the dollar held steady against foreign currencies.
