<HEAD>Court Again Blocks Partial Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court has ordered The <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> to delay their partial merger, which could have begun as early as this weekend, as the judges consider whether the deal should be scrapped altogether. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> late Thursday ordered a stay in an order by Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> allowing the newspapers to merge their business, production and circulation department's under an exception to federal antitrust laws. <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Citizens for an <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, an organization of advertisers and readers opposed to the newspapers' joint operating agreement, had asked for the extension in a motion filed earlier in the day. The court ordered the delay to gain time to study the complex case, the court clerk's office said. The group last month successfully blocked the immediate merger of the newspapers' business and production departments in a challenge to a decision by then-Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> allowing the joint operating agreement under the Newspaper Preservation Act. The temporary stay granted by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> forced the newspapers to recall laid-off employees and quickly alter printing plans. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Revercomb </PERSON> on Wednesday rejected the challenge and said he would allow the order staying the partial merger to expire at 7:15 p.m. on Saturday. The appeals court's order Thursday means the combination will not proceed on that schedule. The newspapers had not said how quickly then could have begun joint production under the agreement after expiration of the earlier stay. Free Press Publisher <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> this week said the newspapers would begin the operation as soon as they were legally cleared to do so. The court issued its own order staying <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s decision rather than granting the opponents' request for a stay, thereby gaining time to study the case without seeming to accept the contentions of either side. After the <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Citizens group made its request, Assistant Attorney General <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolton </PERSON> filed an eight-page brief with the appeals court opposing any stay of the agreement. The opponents of the merger `` have fallen far short of their burden of showing that the attorney general acted so mistakenly that his decision can be labeled irrational,'' said <PERSON> Bolton </PERSON>'s brief. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON>, an attorney for <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Citizens, said after the appeal was filed that his clients could show a stay was appropriate because a lower court judge, in granting the earlier stay, had agreed that allowing the merger to proceed prior to a court ruling would produce `` irreparable injury'' and be contrary to the public interest. Opponents of the agreement argued that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> had ignored findings that the Free Press was not a failing newspaper and that financial losses by it and the News were caused by management decisions rather than being inherent to the marketplace. <PERSON> Revercomb </PERSON> rejected that contention, saying that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> had reasonably found that the Free Press would have already failed were it not owned by a large corporate parent, <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> had no comment on the appeal, said <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlatter </PERSON>, manager of corporate communications <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> also declined comment. `` We're simply waiting to see what the appeals court does,'' said <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibbons </PERSON>, public affairs manager. The News referred inquires to <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION>. The general manager of the Free Press, <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, said today, `` The stay that was issued is really an administrative stay, and it's only issued for the convenience of the court to take some time to look at the request for the stay,'' The delay `` just gives the judges a couple of days to look at the filings'' and has no bearing on the merits of the case. The merger of the newspapers' business, advertising, circulation and production departments would result in layoffs of 600 to 800 employees. The Free Press had a daily circulation last year of 638,720, compared with the News' 678,720, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Audit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circulation </ORGANIZATION>. On Sundays, the News held a slightly larger lead, 839,319 to 724,342.
