<HEAD>Dollar Stuck in Tight Range in Europe, Gold Falls Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar finished mixed Friday after remaining in a tight range during the European session, reflecting indecision among market participants about the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency's direction. Gold prices tumbled as much as $ 6.50 an ounce in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, hurt by what bullion brokers called investor disappointment with the precious metal's declining value over the last few weeks. Traders said the dollar spent the day in a range of about 1.8700 West German marks to 1.8780 marks, roughly the same range it was confined to Thursday. One trader said the market `` just does n't have an idea which way to push it. Traders said fear of central bank intervention combined with internal market resistance is preventing the dollar from rising, but that the recent news of an improvement in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit is supporting the currency. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost $ 1.6758 to buy one pound, vs. $ 1.6675 late Thursday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> compared with late Thursday included: 1.8763 West German marks, down from 1.8775; 1.5835 Swiss francs, up from 1.5820; 6.3795 French francs, up from 6.3790; 2.1151 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1160; 1,398.50 Italian lire, down from 1,398.87; 1.2232 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2225. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where the business day ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s begins, the dollar rose 0.31 yen to a closing 133.76 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 134.25 yen. Gold fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to $ 412 a troy ounce, compared with $ 417.75 late Thursday. Brokers said that because of the metal's failure to stay above the psychologically important level of $ 420, many gold holders were selling. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold closed $ 411 compared with $ 417.50 late Thursday. Earlier in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 3.61 to close at $ 419.84. Silver bullion prices fell on the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> market $ 6.40 a troy ounce, compared with $ 6.44 Thursday.
