<HEAD>Eastern Airlines Pilots Take Case to Wall Street</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> pilots, locked in a battle with management, told financial analysts Friday the ailing airline may have to be sold or merged with sister carrier <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. `` Anywhere you look you can see the systematic destruction of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Vician </PERSON>, vice chairman of the Master Executive Council of the Eastern pilots' union. `` This airline can not be turned around by labor concessions alone.'' <PERSON> Vician </PERSON> said the union sees three possible options at this point: negotiation of an acceptable contract agreement between the pilots and <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> management, a merger between <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> or a buyout of Eastern by an outside entity. Miami-based <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>, a non-union carrier, are both subsidiaries of giant <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Eastern continues to sustain heavy losses, posting a net loss of $ 89.8 million in the second quarter Eastern employees have accused <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> of siphoning off cash, in the form of management fees, rents on planes and airport gates and commissions on fuel purchases, from <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> into its parent company, The pilots union and <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> management are scheduled to meet in contract negotiations by the end of the month. While <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> continues to seek cuts in labor costs, it has indicated it could seek to freeze the pilots' wages and cut costs through attrition and longer flying hours. The pilots may try to build `` fence agreements'' into the contract, such as one allowing them to unionize <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> pilots, according to union sources. The airline laid off 4,000 employees early this month. A federal judge in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> had ruled Eastern could not lay off unionized personnel. But the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> later dissolved the order, saying the carrier would have to post a $ 4.7 million bond to cover a month of paychecks should the unions win their case. Members of the Machinists union at Eastern began voting Friday on a contract that would cut pay for mechanics by as much as 20 percent, with even sharper cuts for less-skilled workers. It is unusual for a union to advocate a merger. But <PERSON> Vician </PERSON> and <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON> <PERSON> Kupersmith </PERSON>, an accountant at <ORGANIZATION> Touche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ross </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> who is working with the pilots, told the analysts a merger between <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> would remove the contentious issue of cash transfers out of Eastern. `` There is no good merger in the -LRB- airline -RRB- industry with responsibility to the employees,'' <PERSON> Vician </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> after the meeting. `` It would not be our first choice.'' As for another possible approach, a takeover of Eastern by the pilots with outside financial backing, <PERSON> Vician </PERSON> said his union has been advised that `` that is a futile effort.''
</TEXT>
