tance at the end of the 15-year period. The <ORGANIZATION> Omaha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> merged on July 6, forming the <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Omaha </ORGANIZATION>, which provides comprehensive banking services to farmers and ranchers in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>. The 1987 law created the board to work with troubled FCS institutions. It was chartered on Jan. 21, 1988, and comprises three members: Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON>, Acting Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> McPherson </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> farmer <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Erwin </PERSON>.
