<HEAD>Gold Slumps to 18-Month Low; Dollar Mixed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Republic in 3rd graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gold prices tumbled nearly $ 7 a troy ounce in busy trading Friday to the lowest point in 18 months, hurt by a tide of fresh selling and evidence that inflation remains subdued. The dollar was mixed in slow trading. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> quoted gold bullion at $ 411.75 as of 4 p.m. EDT, down $ 6.75 from its level of late Thursday and down $ 18.05 from late Wednesday, a combined loss of more than 4 percent. Gold had not traded that low since March 1987. Bullion brokers said people who had hoarded gold as a hedge against inflation were becoming impatient and exasperated because the metal had been falling in value relative to some interest-bearing investments. `` These people are disappointed and shocked and adding fuel to the fire,'' said <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON>, vice president and bullion dealer at <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. `` The more selling that comes in, the more these people are in a panic.'' Moreover, recent economic statistics in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> suggest inflation will not rise nearly as much has some gold holders had expected, heightening prospects that the metal could test $ 400 an ounce. Gold has not been that low since December 1986. `` There's been a lot of new selling,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON>, senior gold trader at <ORGANIZATION> MTB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> metals concern. `` The feeling is you might see $ 400 gold real soon here. I think next week you'll see $ 400 gold.'' <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Schoen </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> Midland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGA