<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge, saying a quick ruling would be `` almost shooting from the hip,'' declined to make a decision Friday on whether to allow the $ 2.5 billion merger of Lucky and Alpha Beta to proceed. After three hours of arguments by attorneys, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenyon </PERSON> asked for more data on the `` relevant market area'' affected by the proposed merger. Attorneys said they could supply the information by Wednesday and <PERSON> Kenyon </PERSON> said he would rule soon after that. <PERSON> Kenyon </PERSON> left in place a temporary restraining order which bars completion of the acquisition of Lucky by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>, parent company of <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beta </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> has filed suit to stop the merger. He claims that transaction coupled with the recent merger of <ORGANIZATION> Safeway </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Vons </ORGANIZATION> supermarkets will decrease competition and mean higher prices for <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> consumers. Deputy Attorney General <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> Horne </PERSON> argued that the merger violates the Clayton Antitrust Act and said that the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has never approved a merger between two such gigantic market chains. He suggested the merger will virtually eliminate `` mom and pop grocery stores,'' which will be unable to compete against the giants. `` Without the entry of signficant competititors there will be no competition in this state if this merger is allowed to go through,'' <PERSON> Horne </PERSON> said. Attorney <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothman </PERSON>, representing <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION>, the parent company of <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beta </ORGANIZATION>, said the consumer will benefit because <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beta </ORGANIZATION> plans to adopt Lucky's low-price structure. When <PERSON> Kenyon </PERSON> expressed skepticism about whether low prices would last, <PERSON> Rothman </PERSON> responded that if the chain raised prices, `` Everyone else in the marketplace would cut our heart out.''
